# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: community-of-the-ark
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The town is located on a small bluff above the river Orb, about ten kilometres (six miles) from the Mediterranean coast and 75 kilometres (47 miles) southwest of Montpellier.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] At Béziers, the Canal du Midi passes over the river Orb by means of the *Pont-canal de l'Orb*, an aqueduct claimed to be the first of its kind.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers is one of the oldest cities in France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Research published in March 2013 shows that the ancient Greek colony of Béziers dates from 575 BCE, making it older than Agde (Greek Agathe Tyche, founded in 525 BCE) and slightly younger than Marseille (Greek Massalia, founded in 600 BCE).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The site has been occupied since Neolithic times, before the influx of Celts.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Roman *Betarra* was on the road that linked Provence with Iberia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The Romans refounded the city as a new *colonia* for veterans in 36–35 BCE and called it *Colonia Julia Baeterrae Septimanorum*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Stones from the Roman amphitheatre were used to construct the city wall during the third century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] A *dolium* discovered in an excavation near Rome is marked, "I am a wine from Baeterrae and I am five years old." Another is simply marked, "white wine of Baeterrae." Béziers was conquered by the Muslims and remained part of Islamic Iberia between 720 and 752.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] From the 10th to the 12th centuries, Béziers was the centre of a Viscountship of Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The viscounts ruled most of the coastal plain around Béziers, including the town of Agde.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] They also controlled the major east–west route through Languedoc, which roughly follows the old Roman Via Domitia, with the two key bridges over the Orb at Béziers and over the Hérault at Saint-Thibéry.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] After the death of Viscount William around 990, the viscounty passed to his daughter Garsendis and her husband, Count Raimond-Roger of Carcassonne (d. c.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] It was then ruled by their son Peter-Raimond (d. c.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] 1067), both of whom were also counts of Carcassonne.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Roger died without issue and Béziers passed to his sister Ermengard and her husband Raimond-Bertrand Trencavel.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The Trencavels ruled for the next 142 years, until the Albigensian Crusade, a formal crusade (holy war) authorised by Pope Innocent III.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers was a stronghold of Catharism, which the Catholic Church condemned as heretical and exterminated in the Albigensian Crusade.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The crusaders reached Béziers on 21 July 1209.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers' Catholics were given an ultimatum to hand over the heretics or leave before the crusaders besieged the city and to "avoid sharing their fate and perishing with them".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] However, many refused and resisted with the Cathars.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The town was sacked the following day and in the bloody massacre no one was spared, not even Catholic priests and those who took refuge in the churches.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] One of the commanders of the crusade was the Papal legate Arnaud-Amaury (or Arnald Amalaricus, abbot of Citeaux).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] When asked by a crusader how to tell Catholics from Cathars once they had taken the city, the abbot supposedly replied, "*Caedite eos.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Novit enim Dominus qui sunt eius*" ("Kill them all, for the Lord knoweth them that are His").
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] (This oft-quoted phrase is sourced from Caesarius of Heisterbach along with a story of all the heretics who desecrated a copy of the Gospels and threw it down from the town's walls.) Amalric's own version of the siege, described in his letter to Pope Innocent III in August 1209 (col.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The invaders burned the Cathedral of Saint Nazaire, which collapsed on those who had taken refuge inside.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] By some accounts, none were left alive—by others, there were a handful of survivors.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Despite the massacre, the city was repopulated.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] A few parts of the Romanesque cathedral of St-Nazaire had survived the carnage, and repairs started in 1215.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The restoration, along with that of the rest of the city, continued until the 15th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers became part of the royal domain in 1247.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] A school of troubadours arose at Béziers in the 1260s–80s, with four poets: Bernart d'Auriac, Joan Esteve, Joan Miralhas, and Raimon Gaucelm.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The latter three were natives of Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] All four lived there and were members of the urban middle class and not courtesans: Miralhas was possibly a potter and Bernart a teacher.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] They wrote in Occitan but supported the French king Louis IX and the French aristocracy against the native Occitan nobility, and have been described as "gallicised".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Raimon Gaucelm supported the Eighth Crusade and even wrote a *planh*, the only known one of its kind, to a burgher of Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Joan Esteve and Bernart both composed in support of the French in the Aragonese Crusade.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] These poets are a shining example of the transformation of Occitania in the aftermath of the Albigensian Crusade, but also of the ability of troubadours to survive it.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers was not damaged in the Hundred Years' War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 8 September 1381, a riot broke out at the seat of the municipal council, rioters setting the Town House on fire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The councillors tried to take refuge in the tower, but fire spread there as well, and they all died either by fire or in jumping from the tower to the square.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] King Charles IX passed through the city during his royal tour of France (1564–1566), accompanied by the Court and the great men of the kingdom: his brother Henry, the Duke of Anjou, his distant cousin Henri of Navarre, and the Cardinal of Bourbon with the Cardinal of Lorraine.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In 1551, Béziers became the seat of a seneschal, being removed from the jurisdiction of the seneschals of Carcassonne.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The city served as a rear base during various wars of the modern period, especially those against the Habsburgs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] During the War of the Spanish Succession, the British in 1710 landed at Sète and moved to within a few kilometres of Béziers, before being repulsed by the Duke of Roquelaure.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers was at the heart of the Montmorency Revolt in 1632.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] It was in Béziers that Gaston d'Orléans and Henri II de Montmorency, Governor of Languedoc, met at the beginning of the rebellion.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] It was also here that the king, by the Edict of Béziers (October 1632), abolished the privileges of the province.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] During the 18th century, Béziers prospered, notably thanks to the cultivation of vines which enabled it to become an important centre for alcohol trading.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] During the French Revolution, citizens of Béziers met in a revolutionary society created in May 1790 and numbering up to 400 members.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] It had several successive names: first, "The Literary and Patriotic Cabinet", a name still derived from the social life of the Ancien Régime; it then became "Society of the Friends of the Constitution and Liberty".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] From 1790 to 1800, Béziers was the chief town of the district of Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The city did not take part in the Girondin ("Federalist") movement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In the repression following Louis Napoléon's coup d'état in 1851, troops fired on and killed Republican protesters in Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Others were condemned to death or transported to Guiana, including Casimir Peret, the mayor at the time, who died at sea attempting to escape from there.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In the Place de la Révolution a plaque and a monument by Jean Antoine Injalbert commemorates these events.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] While elsewhere in France, the area planted with vines was decreasing, it increased in the departments of Aude, Gard, Hérault and the Pyrénées-Orientales.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Together, these supplied some 40% of French wine production.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Haut Languedoc, and more particularly the Biterrois and Béziers, proclaimed themselves to be "The World Capital of Wine" and grew rapidly.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Large landowners, coming from industry, finance or the liberal professions, gained possession of immense vineyards.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] There was also a growing foreign competition, with smuggled wines appearing on the market.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In 1892, the winegrowers of the Midi demanded "The restoration and enforcement of customs duties".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] But the market remained partly held by wines made from imported dried grapes (such as grapes from Corinth ), and wines called "wet" (adulterated with water).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Though the vintners attached great importance to this unfair competition, in fact it did not represent more than 5% of the market.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 12 May 1907, no less than 150,000 protesters gathered in Béziers with the declared aim of "Defending the Southern Viticulture".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The crowd spilled into Paul-Riquet and the Champ-de-Mars.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The slogans on the banners Proclaimed: "Victory or death!
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Enough of talking, the time has come for action!
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The demonstrators, who came from more than 200 communes, were joined by numerous Biterrois employees and shopkeepers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] There were some minor incidents during the dispersal of the demonstrators.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 16 May, the Béziers municipal council, of Radical and Socialist tendency, resigned.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The police station and the town hall façade were set on fire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Alerted, Georges Clemenceau decided to launch a counterattack.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The 17th regiment of line infantry, composed of reservists and conscripts, was on his orders transferred from Béziers to Agde on 18 June 1907.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On the evening of 20 June, learning of the Narbonne shooting, about 500 soldiers of the 6th company of the 17th regiment mutinied, plundered the armory and headed for Béziers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] They traveled about twenty kilometers by night.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 21 June, in the early morning, they arrived in town.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] They were warmly welcomed by the Biterrois, "fraternizing with the demonstrators, and peacefully opposing the armed forces".
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The soldiers sat down on the Allées Paul Riquet and the population offered them wine and food.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The South was on the brink of insurrection.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In Paulhan, the railway was taken out of commission by protesters who stopped a military convoy sent to quell the mutineers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In Lodève, the sub-prefect was taken hostage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The military authorities were not ready to accept this mutiny, apprehensive that the example of the 17th regiment would give similar ideas to other regiments in the region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In Paris, the Republic trembled, as Clemenceau had to face a vote of no confidence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] However, he survived by letting the military command urgently negotiate with the mutineers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] In the afternoon, after obtaining a guarantee that no sanctions will be imposed on them, the 17th soldiers put down their arms and marched to the station under escort, without any major incident.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 22 June, they returned by train to their barracks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Clemenceau announced the end of the mutiny and gained a parliamentary vote of confidence by 327 votes to 223.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] On 23 June, a law was finally passed, which repressed the massive chaptalisation of the wines.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Negotiations and the scale of the movement prevented collective punishment: the mutineers of the 17th were assigned to Gafsa (Tunisia), a place where soldiers were often sent for "disciplinary companies", but these soldiers remained outside this framework, and were under ordinary military status.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] There was therefore no penal sanction for the revolt of the 17th, contrary to the legend that developed on this subject.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] However, during the First World War, haunted by their reputation as deserters, many of them were sent to the front line, particularly in the bloody assaults of 1914.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Before 1963, wine was the only way to bring money into the area.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers city is now a part of economic plan Mission Racine.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers has a Mediterranean climate (Köppen climate classification *Csa*).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The average annual temperature in Béziers is 15.1 °C (59.2 °F).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The average annual rainfall is 595.7 mm (23.45 in) with October as the wettest month.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The temperatures are highest on average in July, at around 24.1 °C (75.4 °F), and lowest in January, at around 7.5 °C (45.5 °F).
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The highest temperature ever recorded in Béziers was 42.0 °C (107.6 °F) on 7 July 1982; the coldest temperature ever recorded was −16.0 °C (3.2 °F) on 16 January 1985.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The inhabitants of Béziers are known as *Biterrois*, after *Baeterrae*, the Roman name for the town.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Other sights in the area include the Oppidum d'Ensérune archaeological site and the Étang de Montady, a marsh drained in 1247 to create a field and irrigation system which is visible from the Oppidum d'Ensérune.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers is a principal centre of the Languedoc viticulture and wine making industries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] Béziers' rugby union team is AS Béziers Hérault, the football team is AS Béziers (2007) which plays in Championnat National 2.
[src:community-of-the-ark/beziers] The women's volleyball team, the Béziers Angels, won the national LNV Ligue A Féminine in 2018.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Various forms of civil disobedience have been used by prominent activists, such as American women's suffrage leader Susan B.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Anthony in the late 19th century, Egyptian nationalist Saad Zaghloul during the 1910s, and Indian nationalist Mahatma Gandhi in 1920s British India as part of his leadership of the Indian independence movement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Martin Luther King Jr.'s and James Bevel's peaceful nonviolent protests during the civil rights movement in the 1960s United States sometimes contained important aspects of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] An early depiction of civil disobedience is in Sophocles' play *Antigone*, in which Antigone, one of the daughters of former King of Thebes, Oedipus, defies Creon, the current King of Thebes, who is trying to stop her from giving her brother Polynices a proper burial.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] She gives a stirring speech in which she tells him that she must obey her conscience rather than human law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] She is not at all afraid of the death he threatens her with (and eventually carries out), but she is afraid of how her conscience will smite her if she does not do this.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Following the Peterloo massacre of 1819, the poet Percy Shelley wrote the political poem *The Mask of Anarchy* later that year, that begins with the images of what he thought to be the unjust forms of authority of his time—and then imagines the stirrings of a new form of social action.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] According to Ashton Nichols, it is perhaps the first modern statement of the principle of nonviolent protest.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] A version was taken up by the author Henry David Thoreau in his essay *Civil Disobedience*, and later by Gandhi in his doctrine of *Satyagraha*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Gandhi's Satyagraha was partially influenced and inspired by Shelley's nonviolence in protest and political action.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In particular, it is known that Gandhi often quoted Shelley's *Mask of Anarchy* to vast audiences during the campaign for a free India.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Thoreau's 1849 essay *Civil Disobedience*, originally titled "Resistance to Civil Government", has had a wide influence on many later practitioners of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The driving idea behind the essay is that citizens are morally responsible for their support of aggressors, even when such support is required by law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In the essay, Thoreau explained his reasons for having refused to pay taxes as an act of protest against slavery and against the Mexican–American War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Pro Public and typically peaceful resistance to political power remained an integral tactic in modern American minority rights politics.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Following this Captain Charles Boycott, the land agent of an absentee landlord in County Mayo, Ireland, was subject to social ostracism organized by the Irish Land League in 1880.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Boycott attempted to evict eleven tenants from his land.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] While Parnell's speech did not refer to land agents or landlords, the tactic was applied to Boycott when the alarm was raised about the evictions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Despite the short-term economic hardship to those undertaking this action, Boycott soon found himself isolated – his workers stopped work in the fields and stables, as well as in his house.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Local businessmen stopped trading with him, and the local postman refused to deliver mail.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The movement spread throughout Ireland and gave rise to the term to Boycott, and eventually led to legal reform and support for Irish independence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Egypt saw a massive implementation on a nation-wide movement starting 1914 and peaking in 1919 as the Egyptian Revolution of 1919.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] This was then adopted by other peoples who campaigned against European colonial rule from 1920 onwards.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Zaghloul Pasha, considered the mastermind behind this massive civil disobedience, was a native middle-class, Azhar graduate, political activist, judge, parliamentary and ex-cabinet minister whose leadership brought Christian and Muslim communities together as well as women into the massive protests.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Along with his companions of Wafd Party, who have achieved an independence of Egypt and a first constitution in 1923.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Civil disobedience is one of the many ways people have revolted against what they deem to be unfair laws.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Henry David Thoreau's 1849 essay "Resistance to Civil Government" was eventually renamed "Essay on Civil Disobedience".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] After his landmark lectures were published in 1866, the term began to appear in numerous sermons and lectures relating to slavery and the war in Mexico.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Thus, by the time Thoreau's lectures were first published under the title "Civil Disobedience", in 1866, four years after his death, the term had achieved fairly widespread usage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It has been argued that the term "civil disobedience" has always suffered from ambiguity and in modern times, become utterly debased.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Marshall Cohen notes, "It has been used to describe everything from bringing a test-case in the federal courts to taking aim at a federal official.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] He encourages a distinction between lawful protest demonstration, nonviolent civil disobedience, and violent civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In seeking an active form of civil disobedience, one may choose to deliberately break certain laws, such as by forming a peaceful blockade or occupying a facility illegally, though sometimes violence has been known to occur.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Often there is an expectation to be attacked or even beaten by the authorities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Protesters often undergo training in advance on how to react to arrest or to attack.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Civil disobedience is usually defined as pertaining to a citizen's relation to the state and its laws, as distinguished from a constitutional impasse, in which two public agencies, especially two equally sovereign branches of government, conflict.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] For instance, if the head of government of a country were to refuse to enforce a decision of that country's highest court, it would not be civil disobedience, since the head of government would act in his or her capacity as public official rather than private citizen.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] This definition is disputed by Thoreau's political philosophy on the conscience vs. the collective.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The person is the final judge of right and wrong.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] More than this, since only people act, only a person can act unjustly.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] When the government knocks on the door, it is a person in the form of a postman or tax collector whose hand hits the wood.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Before Thoreau's imprisonment, when a confused taxman had wondered aloud about how to handle his refusal to pay, Thoreau had advised, "Resign".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] If a man chose to be an agent of injustice, then Thoreau insisted on confronting him with the fact that he was making a choice.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] He admits that government may express the will of the majority but it may also express nothing more than the will of elite politicians.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Even a good form of government is "liable to be abused and perverted before the people can act through it".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] If a government did express the voice of most people, this would not compel the obedience of those who disagree with what is said.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The majority may be powerful but it is not necessarily right.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In his 1971 book, *A Theory of Justice*, John Rawls described civil disobedience as "a public, non-violent, conscientious yet political act contrary to law usually done with the aim of bringing about change in the law or policies of the government".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some theories of civil disobedience hold that civil disobedience is only justified against governmental entities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Brownlee argues that disobedience in opposition to the decisions of non-governmental agencies such as trade unions, banks, and private universities can be justified if it reflects "a larger challenge to the legal system that permits those decisions to be taken".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The same principle, she argues, applies to breaches of law in protest against international organizations and foreign governments.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It is usually recognized that lawbreaking, if it is not done publicly, at least must be publicly announced to constitute civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] But Stephen Eilmann argues that if it is necessary to disobey rules that conflict with morality, we might ask why disobedience should take the form of public civil disobedience rather than simply covert lawbreaking.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] If a lawyer wishes to help a client overcome legal obstacles to securing their natural rights, he might, for instance, find that assisting in fabricating evidence or committing perjury is more effective than open disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] This assumes that common morality does not have a prohibition on deceit in such situations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] There have been debates as to whether civil disobedience must necessarily be non-violent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] *Black's Law Dictionary* includes nonviolence in its definition of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Christian Bay's encyclopedia article states that civil disobedience requires "carefully chosen and legitimate means", but holds that they do not have to be non-violent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Civil disobedients' refraining from violence is also said to help preserve society's tolerance of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Zinn rejects any "easy and righteous dismissal of violence", noting that Thoreau, the popularizer of the term civil disobedience, approved of the armed insurrection of John Brown.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] He also notes that some major civil disobedience campaigns which have been classified as non-violent, such as the Birmingham campaign, have actually included elements of violence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Non-revolutionary civil disobedience is a simple disobedience of laws on the grounds that they are judged "wrong" by a person's conscience, or as part of an effort to render certain laws ineffective, to cause their repeal, or to exert pressure to get one's political wishes on some other issue.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Revolutionary civil disobedience is more of an active attempt to overthrow a government (or to change cultural traditions, social customs or religious beliefs).
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Revolution does not have to be political, i.e.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] "cultural revolution", it simply implies sweeping and widespread change to a section of the social fabric.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Gandhi's acts have been described as revolutionary civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It has been claimed that the Hungarians under Ferenc Deák directed revolutionary civil disobedience against the Austrian government.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Thoreau also wrote of civil disobedience accomplishing "peaceable revolution".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Howard Zinn, Harvey Wheeler, and others have identified the right espoused in the US Declaration of Independence to "alter or abolish" an unjust government to be a principle of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The earliest recorded incidents of collective civil disobedience took place during the Roman Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Unarmed Jews gathered in the streets to prevent the installation of pagan images in the Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In modern times, some activists who commit civil disobedience as a group collectively refuse to sign bail until certain demands are met, such as favourable bail conditions, or the release of all the activists.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] There have also been many instances of solitary civil disobedience, such as that committed by Thoreau, but these sometimes go unnoticed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Thoreau, at the time of his arrest, was not yet a well-known author, and his arrest was not covered in any newspapers in the days, weeks and months after it happened.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The tax collector who arrested him rose to higher political office, and Thoreau's essay was not published until after the end of the Mexican War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Civil disobedients have chosen a variety of different illegal acts.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Bedau also notes, though, that the very harmlessness of such entirely symbolic illegal protests toward public policy goals may serve a propaganda purpose.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Julia Butterfly Hill lived in Luna, a 180-foot (55 m)-tall, 600-year-old California Redwood tree for 738 days, preventing its felling.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In cases where the criminalized behaviour is pure speech, civil disobedience can consist simply of engaging in the forbidden speech.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] An example is WBAI's broadcasting of the bit "Filthy Words" from a George Carlin comedy album, which eventually led to the 1978 Supreme Court case of *FCC v.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Threatening government officials is a way to express defiance toward the government and unwillingness to stand for its policies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] More generally, protesters of particular victimless crimes often see fit to openly commit that crime.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Laws against public nudity, for instance, have been protested by going naked in public, and laws against cannabis consumption have been protested by openly possessing it and using it at cannabis rallies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some forms of civil disobedience, such as illegal boycotts, refusals to pay taxes, draft dodging, distributed denial-of-service attacks, and sit-ins, make it more difficult for a system to function.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In this way, they might be considered coercive; coercive disobedience has the effect of exposing the enforcement of laws and policies, and it has even operated as an aesthetic strategy in contemporary art practice.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Brownlee notes that "although civil disobedients are constrained in their use of coercion by their conscientious aim to engage in moral dialogue, nevertheless they may find it necessary to employ limited coercion to get their issue onto the table".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The Plowshares organization temporarily closed GCSB Waihopai by padlocking the gates and using sickles to deflate one of the large domes covering two satellite dishes.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Electronic civil disobedience can include web site defacements, redirects, denial-of-service attacks, information theft and data leaks, illegal web site parodies, virtual sit-ins, and virtual sabotage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It is distinct from other kinds of hacktivism in that the perpetrator openly reveals his identity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Virtual actions rarely succeed in completely shutting down their targets, but they often generate media attention.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] As civil disobedience is intentionally breaking the law, people engaging in civil disobedience can expect to be arrested, criminally charged, tried, and legally punished for breaking the law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Protestors have to make choices about how to respond to each of these results.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some disciplines of civil disobedience hold that the protester must submit to arrest and cooperate with the authorities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Others advocate falling limp or resisting arrest, especially when it will hinder the police from effectively responding to a mass protest.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Many of the same decisions and principles that apply in other criminal investigations and arrests arise also in civil disobedience cases.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] For example, the suspect may need to decide whether to grant a consent search of his property and whether to talk to police officers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It is generally agreed within the legal community, and is often believed within the activist community, that a suspect's talking to criminal investigators can serve no useful purpose and may be harmful.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some civil disobedients are compelled to respond to investigators' questions, sometimes by a misunderstanding of the legal ramifications or a fear of seeming rude.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Also, some civil disobedients seek to use the arrest as an opportunity to make an impression on the officers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Other civil disobedients who favour the existence of government still do not believe in the legitimacy of their particular government or do not believe in the legitimacy of a particular law it has enacted.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Anarchistic civil disobedients do not believe in the legitimacy of any government, so see no need to accept punishment for a violation of criminal law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] An important decision for civil disobedients is whether to plead guilty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] There is much debate on this point, as some believe that it is a civil disobedient's duty to submit to the punishment prescribed by law, while others believe that defending oneself in court will increase the possibility of changing the unjust law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] It has also been argued that either choice is compatible with the spirit of civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] ACT UP's Civil Disobedience Training handbook states that a civil disobedient who pleads guilty is essentially stating, "Yes, I committed the act of which you accuse me.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] I don't deny it; in fact, I am proud of it.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] I feel I did the right thing by violating this particular law; I am guilty as charged", but that pleading not guilty sends a message of, "Guilt implies wrong-doing.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] I may have violated some specific laws, but I am guilty of doing no wrong.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] I, therefore, plead not guilty." A plea of no contest is sometimes regarded as a compromise between the two.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] One defendant accused of illegally protesting nuclear power, when asked to enter his plea, stated, "I plead for the beauty that surrounds us"; this is known as a "creative plea", and will usually be interpreted as a plea of not guilty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] When the Committee for Non-Violent Action sponsored a protest in August 1957, at the Camp Mercury nuclear test site near Las Vegas, Nevada, 13 of the protesters attempted to enter the test site knowing that they faced arrest.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] At an announced time, one by one they crossed a line and were immediately arrested.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] They were put on a bus and taken to the Nye County seat of Tonopah, Nevada, and arraigned for trial before the local Justice of the Peace, that afternoon.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] A civil rights attorney, Francis Heisler, had volunteered to defend the accused, advising them to plead *nolo contendere* rather than guilty or not guilty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] They were found guilty and given suspended sentences, conditional on not reentering the test site.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Sometimes the prosecution proposes a plea bargain to civil disobedients, as in the case of the Camden 28, in which the defendants were offered an opportunity to plead guilty to one misdemeanour count and receive no jail time.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In some mass arrest situations, the activists decide to use solidarity tactics to secure the same plea bargain for everyone.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] But some activists have opted to enter a blind plea, pleading guilty without any plea agreement in place.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some civil disobedience defendants choose to make a defiant speech, or a speech explaining their actions, in allocution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Burgos-Andujar*, a defendant who was involved in a movement to stop military exercises by trespassing on US Navy property argued to the court in allocution that "the ones who are violating the greater law are the members of the Navy".
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] As a result, the judge increased her sentence from 40 to 60 days.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] This action was upheld because, according to the US Court of Appeals for the First Circuit, her statement suggested a lack of remorse, an attempt to avoid responsibility for her actions, and even a likelihood of repeating her illegal actions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some of the other allocution speeches given by the protesters complained about mistreatment from government officials.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] During the Vietnam War era, the Chicago Eight used a political defence, but Benjamin Spock used a technical defence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In countries such as the United States, whose laws guarantee the right to a jury trial but do not excuse lawbreaking for political purposes, some civil disobedients seek jury nullification.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Over the years, this has been made more difficult by court decisions such as *Sparf v.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] United States*, which held that the judge need not inform jurors of their nullification prerogative, and *United States v.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Dougherty*, which held that the judge need not allow defendants to openly seek jury nullification.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] British judge Lord Hoffman writes that "In deciding whether or not to impose punishment, the most important consideration would be whether it would do more harm than good.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] This means that the objector has no right not to be punished.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] "When it comes to punishment, the court should take into account their personal convictions", he said.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] In addition to legal action, civil disobedients may be affected socially.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] For example, student protesters may be suspended or expelled from school.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Civil disobedients may be disowned by or become estranged from their families.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Some employers may prefer to hire people who did not engage in civil disobedience or fire employees who do.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Governments have generally not recognized the legitimacy of civil disobedience or viewed political objectives as an excuse for breaking the law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Specifically, the law usually distinguishes between criminal motive and criminal intent; the offender's motives or purposes may be admirable and praiseworthy, but his intent may still be criminal.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] For example, a protester may be *motivated by* a desire to increase awareness about an injustice and *intend* to block traffic on a street, and it is the intention, rather than the motivation, that is criminally significant.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] One theory is that, while disobedience may be helpful, any great amount of it undermines the law by encouraging general disobedience which is neither conscientious nor of social benefit.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Therefore, conscientious lawbreakers must be punished.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] During the Vietnam War, courts typically refused to excuse the perpetrators of illegal protests from punishment on the basis of their challenging the legality of the Vietnam War; the courts ruled it was a political question.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] The necessity defence has sometimes been used as a shadow defence by civil disobedients to deny guilt without denouncing their politically motivated acts, and to present their political beliefs in the courtroom.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Schoon* have greatly curtailed the availability of the political necessity defence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Likewise, when Carter Wentworth was charged for his role in the Clamshell Alliance's 1977 illegal occupation of the Seabrook Station Nuclear Power Plant, the judge instructed the jury to disregard his competing harms defence, and he was found guilty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Along with giving the offender his just deserts, achieving crime control via incapacitation and deterrence is a major goal of criminal punishment.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Michael Bayles argues that if a person violates a law to create a test case as to the constitutionality of a law, and then wins his case, then that act did not constitute civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Breaking the law for self-gratification, as in the case of a cannabis user who does not direct his act at securing the repeal of amendment of the law, is not civil disobedience.
[src:community-of-the-ark/civil-disobedience] Likewise, a protester who attempts to escape punishment by committing the crime covertly and avoiding attribution, or by denying having committed the crime, or by fleeing the jurisdiction, is generally not called a civil disobedient.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] A **community** is a social unit (a group of people) with one or more shared socially-significant characteristics, being place, set of norms, culture, religion, values, customs, or identity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Communities may share a sense of place situated in a given geographical area (e.g. a country, village, town, or neighborhood) or in virtual space through communication platforms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Durable good relations that extend beyond immediate genealogical ties also define a sense of community, important to people's identity, practice, and roles in social institutions such as family, home, work, government, society, or humanity at large.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Although communities are usually small relative to personal social ties, "community" may also refer to large-group affiliations such as national communities, international communities, and virtual communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In terms of sociological categories, a community can seem like a sub-set of a social collectivity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In developmental views, a community can emerge out of a collectivity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The English-language word "community" derives from the Old French *comuneté* (Modern French: **communauté**), which comes from the Latin *communitas* "community", "public spirit" (from Latin *communis*, "common").
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Human communities may have intent, belief, resources, preferences, needs, and risks in common, affecting the identity of the participants and their degree of cohesiveness.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Archaeological studies of social communities use the term "community" in two ways, mirroring usage in other areas.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The first meaning is an informal definition of community as a place where people used to live.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In this literal sense it is synonymous with the concept of an ancient settlement—whether a hamlet, village, town, or city.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The second meaning resembles the usage of the term in other social sciences: a community is a group of people living near one another who interact socially.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Social interaction on a small scale can be difficult to identify with archaeological data.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Most reconstructions of social communities by archaeologists rely on the principle that social interaction in the past was conditioned by physical distance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Therefore, a small village settlement likely constituted a social community and spatial subdivisions of cities and other large settlements may have formed communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Archaeologists typically use similarities in material culture—from house types to styles of pottery—to reconstruct communities in the past.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] This classification method relies on the assumption that people or households will share more similarities in the types and styles of their material goods with other members of a social community than they will with outsiders.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In ecology, a community is an assemblage of populations—potentially of different species—interacting with one another.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community ecology is the branch of ecology that studies interactions between and among species.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] It considers how such interactions, along with interactions between species and the abiotic environment, affect social structure and species richness, diversity and patterns of abundance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The two main types of ecological communities are **major** communities, which are self-sustaining and self-regulating (such as a forest or a lake), and **minor** communities, which rely on other communities (like fungi decomposing a log) and are the building blocks of major communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Moreover, we can establish other non-taxonomic subdivisions of biocenosis, such as guilds.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In light of the debate about the meaning of the “European Community,” a series of European philosophers began to raise concerns with how community has been traditionally conceived in the West.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] They questioned whether the closed, exclusionary, and identitarian models of community found in the traditions of Communitarianism in Anglo-American philosophy and Classical Social Theory, were suitable for our globalized world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] However, instead of abandoning the desire to belong in a community, they attempt to reconceptualize community in an open and inclusive manner.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Jean-Luc Nancy is credited with starting this debate with his book *The Inoperative Community*, followed by Maurice Blanchot’s *The Unavowable Community*, Giorgio Agamben’s *The Coming Community*, and Roberto Esposito’s *Communitas*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Jean-Luc Nancy revised his theory of community in *Being Singular Plural*, and he delivered a series of reflections on the terms and motifs of this debate in *The Disavowed Community*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Other books related to this series include Zygmunt Bauman’s *Community*, Greg Bird’s *Containing Community*, Miranda Joseph’s *Against the Romance of Community*, and Alphonso Lingis’ *The Community of Those Who Have Nothing in Common*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The concept of "community" often has a positive semantic connotation, exploited rhetorically by populist politicians and by advertisers to promote feelings and associations of mutual well-being, happiness and togetherness—veering towards an almost-achievable utopian community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In contrast, the epidemiological term "community transmission" can have negative implications, and instead of a "criminal community" one often speaks of a "criminal underworld" or of the "criminal fraternity".
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Early sociological studies identified communities as fringe groups at the behest of local power elites.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Such early academic studies include *Who Governs?* by Robert Dahl as well as the papers by Floyd Hunter on Atlanta.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] At the turn of the 21st century the concept of community was rediscovered by academics, politicians, and activists.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Politicians hoping for a democratic election started to realign with community interests.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The Shona (in Zimbabwe) include ancestral spirits (*midzimu*) in their conceptualisation of the community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In *Gemeinschaft und Gesellschaft* (1887), German sociologist Ferdinand Tönnies described two types of human association: *Gemeinschaft* (usually translated as "community") and *Gesellschaft* ("society" or "association").
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Tönnies proposed the **Gemeinschaft*–**Gesellschaft* dichotomy as a way to think about social ties.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] No group is exclusively one or the other.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] *Gemeinschaft* stress personal social interactions, and the roles, values, and beliefs based on such interactions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] *Gesellschaft* stress indirect interactions, impersonal roles, formal values, and beliefs based on such interactions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] A "sense of community index" (SCI) was developed by Chavis and colleagues, and revised and adapted by others.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Although originally designed to assess sense of community in neighborhoods, the index has been adapted for use in schools, the workplace, and a variety of types of communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Studies conducted by the American Psychological Association indicate that young adults who feel a sense of belonging in a community, particularly small communities, develop fewer psychiatric and depressive disorders than those who do not have the feeling of love and belonging.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The process of learning to adopt the behavior patterns of the community is called socialization.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The most fertile time of socialization is usually the early stages of life, during which individuals develop the skills and knowledge and learn the roles necessary to function within their culture and social environment.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] For some psychologists, especially those in the psychodynamic tradition, the most important period of socialization is between the ages of one and ten.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] But socialization also includes adults moving into a significantly different environment where they must learn a new set of behaviors.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Socialization is influenced primarily by the family, through which children first learn community norms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Other important influences include schools, peer groups, people, mass media, the workplace, and government.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The degree to which the norms of a particular society or community are adopted determines one's willingness to engage with others.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The norms of tolerance, reciprocity, and trust are important "habits of the heart", as de Tocqueville put it, in an individual's involvement in community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] More grassroots efforts, called community building or community organizing, seek to empower individuals and groups of people by providing them with the skills they need to effect change in their own communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] These skills often assist in building political power through the formation of large social groups working for a common agenda.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community development practitioners understand how to work with individuals and affect communities' positions within the context of larger social institutions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Public administrators, in contrast, understand community development in the context of rural and urban development, housing and economic development, and community, organizational and business development.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Formal accredited programs conducted by universities, as part of degree granting institutions, are often used to build a knowledge base to drive curricula in public administration, sociology and community studies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The General Social Survey from the National Opinion Research Center at the University of Chicago and the Saguaro Seminar at the Harvard Kennedy School are examples of national community development in the United States.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The Maxwell School of Citizenship and Public Affairs at Syracuse University in New York State offers core courses in community and economic development, and in areas ranging from non-profit development to US budgeting (federal to local, community funds).
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In the United Kingdom, the University of Oxford has led in providing extensive research in the field through its *Community Development Journal,* used worldwide by sociologists and community development practitioners.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] At the intersection between community *development* and community *building* are a number of programs and organizations with community development tools.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] One example of this is the program of the Asset Based Community Development Institute of Northwestern University.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The institute makes available downloadable tools to assess community assets and make connections between non-profit groups and other organizations that can help in community building.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The Institute focuses on helping communities develop by "mobilizing neighborhood assets" – building from the inside out rather than the outside in.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In the disability field, community building was prevalent in the 1980s and 1990s with roots in John McKnight's approaches.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In *The Different Drum: Community-Making and Peace* (1987) Scott Peck argues that the almost accidental sense of community that exists at times of crisis can be consciously built.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Peck believes that conscious community building is a process of deliberate design based on the knowledge and application of certain rules.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] **Chaos**: People move beyond the inauthenticity of pseudo-community and feel safe enough to present their "shadow" selves.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] **Emptiness**: Moves beyond the attempts to fix, heal and convert of the chaos stage, when all people become capable of acknowledging their own woundedness and brokenness, common to human beings.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] **True community**: Deep respect and true listening for the needs of the other people in this community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In 1991, Peck remarked that building a sense of community is easy but maintaining this sense of community is difficult in the modern world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] The three basic types of community organizing are grassroots organizing, coalition building, and "institution-based community organizing", (also called "broad-based community organizing", an example of which is faith-based community organizing, or Congregation-based Community Organizing).
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community building can use a wide variety of practices, ranging from simple events (e.g., potlucks, small book clubs) to larger-scale efforts (e.g., mass festivals, construction projects that involve local participants rather than outside contractors).
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community building that is geared toward citizen action is usually termed "community organizing".
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In these cases, organized community groups seek accountability from elected officials and increased direct representation within decision-making bodies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Where good-faith negotiations fail, these constituency-led organizations seek to pressure the decision-makers through a variety of means, including picketing, boycotting, sit-ins, petitioning, and electoral politics.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community organizing can focus on more than just resolving specific issues.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Organizing often means building a widely accessible power structure, often with the end goal of distributing power equally throughout the community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Community organizers generally seek to build groups that are open and democratic in governance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Such groups facilitate and encourage consensus decision-making with a focus on the general health of the community rather than a specific interest group.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] If communities are developed based on something they share in common, whether location or values, then one challenge for developing communities is how to incorporate individuality and differences.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Rebekah Nathan suggests in her book, *My Freshman Year*, we are drawn to developing communities totally based on sameness, despite stated commitments to diversity, such as those found on university websites.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] A number of ways to categorize types of community have been proposed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] **Identity-based**: range from the local clique, sub-culture, ethnic group, religious, multicultural or pluralistic civilisation, or the global community cultures of today.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] They may be included as *communities of need* or *identity*, such as disabled persons, or frail aged people.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] **Intentional**: a mix of all three previous types, these are highly cohesive residential communities with a common social or spiritual purpose, ranging from monasteries and ashrams to modern ecovillages and housing cooperatives.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] This involves giving primacy to communities coming together around particular chosen ways of life, such as morally charged or interest-based relations or just living or working in the same location.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] 2. community-life as interest-based, including sporting, leisure-based and business communities which come together for regular moments of engagement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] 3. community-life as proximately-related, where neighbourhood or commonality of association forms a community of convenience, or a community of place (see below).
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] This is where a community is self-consciously treated as an entity to be projected and re-created.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] A nation is one of the largest forms of projected or imagined community.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In these terms, communities can be nested and/or intersecting; one community can contain another—for example a location-based community may contain a number of ethnic communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Both lists above can be used in a cross-cutting matrix in relation to each other.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] In general, virtual communities value knowledge and information as currency or social resource.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] What differentiates virtual communities from their physical counterparts is the extent and impact of "weak ties", which are the relationships acquaintances or strangers form to acquire information through online networks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Relationships among members in a virtual community tend to focus on information exchange about specific topics.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] A survey conducted by Pew Internet and The American Life Project in 2001 found those involved in entertainment, professional, and sports virtual-groups focused their activities on obtaining information.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] An epidemic of bullying and harassment has arisen from the exchange of information between strangers, especially among teenagers, in virtual communities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Despite attempts to implement anti-bullying policies, Sheri Bauman, professor of counselling at the University of Arizona, claims the "most effective strategies to prevent bullying" may cost companies revenue.
[src:community-of-the-ark/communities] Virtual Internet-mediated communities can interact with offline real-life activity, potentially forming strong and tight-knit groups such as QAnon.
[src:community-of-the-ark/community-of-the-ark] During the 1970s, many of the communards, under the leadership of del Vasto, took a leading role in the civil disobedience campaign resisting the proposed extension of the military base on the Larzac plateau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/community-of-the-ark] In the 1970s, the community spread to several locations, including Italy, Spain and Quebec.
[src:community-of-the-ark/community-of-the-ark] In the 1990s, some communities were closed due to conflicts and lack of new members.
[src:community-of-the-ark/community-of-the-ark] In Southern France, the community is still active at La Borie Noble in the mountains of Occitanie, located between Beziers and Millau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/community-of-the-ark] The official site notes that the communities in France, Spain, Italy, Germany and Brazil are still active.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 11 October 1970, during a session of the *Union des démocrates pour la république (UDR)* (Union of democrats for the Republic), André Fanton, secretary of state for defence, gave the first hint that the base would need to be extended.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In 1971 it was chiefly known to French families for its sheepskin glove industry in decline and its infuriating traffic jams.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Popular resistance to the proposal for the military base was immediately evident.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 28 October 1971, Defence Minister Michel Debré made the formal announcement in a televised interview.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The base was to be extended from 3,000 to 17,000 hectares (30 to 170 square kilometers).
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Land would be expropriated from 107 farms in 12 communes around on the small town of La Cavalerie.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The extended base would form one sixth of the total area (100,000 hectares) of the Larzac itself.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In subsequent commentary, Debré pointed out that the project would be "not only vital to the national defence" but would have "a positive impact" on the region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] He cited improvement of the rural electrical distribution system, water supply and roads.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] He stated that the extension was necessitated by saturation of French military bases in general and the need to maintain a military force in proximity to the *Plateau d'Albion*, launch site of ground-ground ballistic nuclear missiles which formed an important element of the French nuclear deterrent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] It was argued by the authorities that the Larzac plateau was sparsely populated, having been substantially depopulated by the so-called "rural exodus", losing two thirds of its population between 1866 and 1968, although since 1968 population had begun to increase due to the "neo-rural" movement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Sheep herders and producers of Roquefort cheese, the most famous product of the region, denied that the project would be a net boost for employment because, as a training camp, it would attract only temporary inhabitants.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] They were also sceptical of the promised economic benefits.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The first notable demonstration took place on 6 November 1971 at Millau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Some 6,000 people assembled in the Place du Mandarous.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] At this point the movement was still local but it attracted a fairly wide spectrum of participants.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The core group were members of long-established and deeply rooted peasant families but there were also many younger farming families, new to the area and in considerable debt to the *Crédit Agricole* bank which had financed their acquisition and exploitation of land.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Many of these relative newcomers belonged to the quasi-religious organisation *Jeunesse Agricole Catholique* (Young Catholic Farmers).
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Institutional religion was influential in reconciling the many divergent views at this point.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Notably, on 7 November 1971 the bishop of Rodez (the Departmental seat of government) announced his opposition to the base extension.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] There was sufficient unanimity, at any rate, for 103 of the 107 people potentially threatened with expropriation to sign a formal contract on 28 March 1972.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The contract expressed solidarity and declared that not a single farmer would be dispossessed against his will.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A further demonstration took place the following 14 July, the national holiday, in Rodez.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] 20,000 people and 70 tractors participated.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The slogan GARDAREM LO LARZAC began to appear all across the region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] It means, loosely, THE LARZAC IS OURS, and significantly it's written in Occitan, the original language of Languedoc which is not used commercially but is cherished by a militant minority.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Suddenly, the defiant peasant resistance to militarism became a political *cause célèbre*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Left-wingers of all types took up the cause.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Socialists, Communists, and Trade Union militants appeared in Millau and in the villages of the Larzac noisily adding their support to a movement that had originally been declared apolitical.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] To these were added Occitanian nationalists, protesting against what they saw as cultural genocide by a colonial power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Further complicating the situation, a rag-tag assortment of hippies and drop-outs attached themselves to the resistance movement, together with protesters whose motives seemed very remote from the interests of sheep husbandry – pro-choice feminists, for example.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Writing in *Le Monde* (25 August 1973), Michel Castaing described the Larzac as "The shop window of protest".
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] This phase of the protest movement culminated in the first mass rally, on 25–26 August 1973, at *Rajal del Guorp* (the name means 'Crow Springs' in occitan,) a natural dolomitic amphitheatre north-west of La Cavalerie.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The location is inside the perimeter of the military base and so holding the rally there was an act of defiance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Between 60,000 and 100,000 people (the latter figure claimed by the organisers assembled to show their support, in a remote site entirely devoid of facilities for refreshment and hygiene).
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The event attracted world attention—speakers at the rally included representatives of revolutionary movements in Chile, Italy and Greece.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Two members of the Irish Republican Army expressed their solidarity with the peasants of the Larzac and declared support for resistance "by whatever means are necessary".
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Police surveillance at this rally was minimal, with a single Gendarmerie helicopter overhead.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A second mass rally at *Rajal del Guorp* took place a year later, 17–18 August 1974.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] This time the organisers claimed even more than 100,000 protesters.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] François Mitterrand made an appearance and was pelted with pebbles by militant Maoists.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Since they happened in mid-summer, at the height of the tourist season, these and other gatherings inevitably had something of the atmosphere of festivals, regardless of the seriousness of their intent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Musical instruments and topless young women were much in evidence and commemorative T-shirts quickly appeared in local markets.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A few concerts were organised, such as that by Graeme Allwright in 1973.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Allwright later wrote a song entitled *Larzac 1975*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Even José Bové referred to those rallies with some pride as "the French Woodstock" but he also recognised that the effect on public relations was decidedly mixed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 25 October 1974, a flock of 60 sheep were transported to Paris and set to grazing on the Champ de Mars, right under the Eiffel Tower.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] To inquiring gendarmes, the shepherds explained that it was publicity for Roquefort cheese.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Earlier, a protest march on Paris had been triggered by the signature of the decree of expropriation in the public interest, on 26 December 1972.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The march began on the following 7 January, with stops at Rodez, Saint-Flour, Clermont-Ferrand, Nevers and Orléans.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] At each stop, marchers were welcomed and lodged by local committees; meetings, rallies, and press conferences were organised.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Police and local authorities were much less welcoming.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The marchers were harassed at every stop-over.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Finally, at Orléans, the procession was blocked by the *Compagnies Républicaines de Sécurité* (CRS, French riot police) and their 26 tractors impounded.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Bernard Lambert, leader of the *Mouvement des Paysans Travailleurs* (Working Peasant Movement), promptly arranged for the loan of 26 tractors belonging to farmers in the Orléans area, the CRS were outflanked and the march proceeded to Paris.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A second Paris march began on 2 December 1978.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] 18 Larzac farmers walked 710 km in 25 stages.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The CRS blocked the centre of Paris but 40,000 supporters rallied on the outskirts, making the largest demonstration of the year.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The final Paris action began on 27 November 1980, at the height of the presidential campaigns of François Mitterrand and Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Mitterrand, notwithstanding his treatment at the hands of militants at *Rajal del Guorp* in 1974, had opposed the base extension.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The action consisted of an encampment, in bitterly cold weather, on the Champ de Mars complete with farm animals, bales of straw, a radio station and a media information bureau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The demonstrators were forcibly removed after a few days but the point had been made.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] As early as 1972, the communard, philosopher and theorist of non-violence Lanza del Vasto had taken an interest in the plight of the Larzac shepherds and farmers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Del Vasto's commune, the Community of the Ark, was nearby on the plateau de l'Escandorgue.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] He and his followers were skilled at civil disobedience, veterans of hunger strikes against the use of torture during the Algerian war and against nuclear weapons.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 19 March Lanza del Vasto began a 15-day hunger strike at La Cavalerie.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] He was joined by four local residents: Etienne Paloc, Pierre Bastide, and Pierre & Christiane Burguière.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Mme Burguière recalled the impact it had on them.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In 2011 she told film-maker Christian Rouaud *"it was amazing, in a moral sense.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] When we came back, I felt I was no longer the same.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Civil disobedience was also partly the motive of the decision to rebuild the ruined stone sheep shelter (*bergerie*) at La Blaquière.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The property belonged to activist Auguste Guiraud and was due for expropriation under the terms of the decree.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 10 June 1973 re-construction began in defiance of the expropriation order and the fact that planning permission had not been granted.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Hundreds of supporters came to join the effort, notably the hippie contingent who had to learn the art and craft of masonry very quickly, with somewhat random results.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] To say that the influx of hippies shocked the locals is an understatement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Marizette Tarlier recalled that it was the first time she'd seen bare-breasted women in public.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The eight months of construction were marked by constant argument and conflict, but the bergerie was finished in February 1974 and stands to this day as a monument to the joint effort.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Another tactic that was used with success was to sell very small parcels of land to many sympathisers, with the aim of making the eventual expropriation as difficult as possible for the bureaucracy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Between 1973 and 1981, 6,180 tiny plots were allocated to 3,500 different people and to make the act of expropriation even more difficult, many of these "landowners" lived abroad.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In 1976, the fight escalated after soldiers blew up Auguste Guiraud's house in La Blaquière during the night.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Miraculously, Guiraud and his seven children were unharmed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 22 June, a group of 22 activists entered the Larzac military base and destroyed 500 documents containing details of the expropriation.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] They were arrested and arraigned in Millau the next day.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] They were sentenced to prison terms varying from three to six months but in fact none actually served more than three weeks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] On 21 October 1977, trials of Larzac activists took place in Millau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A smörgåsbord of charges included disobedience of authority, removal of army property, blocking traffic, etc.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The hearings were much disrupted by the deliberate release of a flock of sheep in the courtroom.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] To run the campaign, an executive committee was formed and put in charge.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Once general assemblies became more frequent, regional committees (Larzac-East, West, North, South and La Cavalerie) were formed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] A rule, never broken over the ten years of the campaign, was that only residents of the Larzac had voting power in the general assemblies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Decisions were normally made by consensus, with the exception of decisions pertaining to negotiations with the government in 1977; these were by democratic vote.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Meetings were held at least weekly for the ten years of the campaign.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The organisers were in frequent contact with other civil disobedience actions elsewhere in France, as well as the anti-nuclear movement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Another *bergerie* was built at the site of the proposed nuclear power station at Plogoff, and the Larzac contributed 20 ewes to the action.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] About 150 committees were formed to encourage and support various political actions, not just in France but in other European countries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] 28 October 1978 saw a national day of action organised by the Larzac committees.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Marches, meetings, and hunger strikes were attended by tens of thousands of sympathisers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In 1975 the movement started its own newspaper, *Gardarem lo Larzac*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] The first edition was published on 6 June and the journal eventually had 4,000 subscribers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In February 1979, local referendums were organised in the surrounding communities of Millau, Creissels, and La Couvertoirade (a medieval city of the Knights Templar.) 88 to 95% of the electorate voted NO to the extension of the military base.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] In May 1980, the *Cour de Cassation*, France's appeal court of last resort, annulled the 66 expropriation proceedings.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Once François Mitterrand was elected President on 10 May 1981, he declared the base extension project formally abandoned in the Council of Ministers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Property already acquired by the State for the project was leased back to the private company *Terres du Larzac* (Larzac Soils).
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Victory was complete but Lanza del Vasto did not live to see it.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] He had died on 5 January, at the age of 79.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] This two-hour documentary features historical film footage and extended interviews with some of those most intimately involved in the fight for the Larzac.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] With remarkable candour and good humour, they look back on the 1971–81 decade nearly 40 years later.
[src:community-of-the-ark/fight-for-the-larzac] Featuring Pierre Bonnefous, José Bové, Pierre & Christiane Burguière, Michel Courtin, Léon Maille, Christian Roqueirol, Vve Marizette Tarlier, Michèle Vincent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Metropolitan France was settled during the Iron Age by Celtic tribes known as Gauls before Rome annexed the area in 51 BC, leading to a distinct Gallo-Roman culture.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the Early Middle Ages, the Franks formed the kingdom of Francia, which became the heartland of the Carolingian Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Treaty of Verdun of 843 partitioned the empire, with West Francia evolving into the Kingdom of France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the High Middle Ages, France was a powerful but decentralised feudal kingdom, but from the mid-14th to the mid-15th centuries, France was plunged into a dynastic conflict with England known as the Hundred Years' War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the 16th century, French culture flourished during the French Renaissance, and a French colonial empire emerged.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Internally, France was dominated by the conflict with the House of Habsburg and the French Wars of Religion between Catholics and Huguenots.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was successful in the Thirty Years' War and further increased its influence during the reign of Louis XIV.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French Revolution of 1789 overthrew the Ancien Régime and produced the Declaration of the Rights of Man, which expresses the nation's ideals to this day.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France reached its political and military zenith in the early 19th century under Napoleon Bonaparte, subjugating much of continental Europe and establishing the First French Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its collapse initiated a period of relative decline during which France endured the Bourbon Restoration until the founding of the French Second Republic, which was succeeded by the Second French Empire upon Napoleon III's takeover.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] His empire collapsed during the Franco-Prussian War in 1870.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This led to the establishment of the French Third Republic, as well as a period of economic prosperity and cultural and scientific flourishing known as the Belle Époque.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was one of the major participants of World War I, from which it emerged victorious at great human and economic cost.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It was among the Allies of World War II, but it surrendered and was occupied by Germany in 1940.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Following its liberation in 1944, the short-lived Fourth Republic was established and later dissolved over the course of the Algerian War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The current Fifth Republic, a semi-presidential system, was formed in 1958 by Charles de Gaulle.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Algeria and most French colonies became independent in the 1960s, with the majority retaining close economic and military ties with France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France retains its centuries-long status as a global centre of art, science, cuisine and philosophy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It hosts the fourth-largest number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites, with 54 in total, and is the world's leading tourist destination, having received 102 million foreign visitors in 2025.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A developed country, France has a high nominal per capita income globally, and its economy ranks among the largest in the world by both nominal GDP and PPP-adjusted GDP.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It is a great power, being one of the five permanent members of the United Nations Security Council and an official nuclear-weapon state.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The country is part of multiple international organisations and forums.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Originally applied to the whole Frankish Empire, the name *France* comes from the Latin *Francia*, or 'realm of the Franks'.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It has been suggested that the meaning 'free' was adopted because after the conquest of Gaul, only Franks were free of taxation or, more generally, because they had the status of freemen in contrast to servants or slaves.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It is traditionally derived from the Proto-Germanic word **frankōn*, which translates to 'javelin' or 'lance' (the throwing axe of the Franks was known as the *francisca*), although these weapons may have been named because of their use by the Franks, not the other way around.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In English, 'France' is pronounced /fræns/ *FRANSS* in American English and /frɑːns/ *FRAHNSS* or /fræns/ *FRANSS* in British English.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The pronunciation with /ɑː/ is mostly confined to accents with the trap–bath split, such as Received Pronunciation, though it can be also heard in some other dialects, such as Cardiff English.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The oldest traces of archaic humans in what is now France date from approximately 1.8 million years ago.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Neanderthals occupied the region into the Upper Paleolithic era but were slowly replaced by *Homo sapiens* around 35,000 BC.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This period witnessed the emergence of cave painting in the Dordogne and Pyrenees, including at Lascaux, dated to c.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] At the end of the Last Glacial Period (10,000 BC), the climate became milder.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From approximately 7,000 BC, this part of Western Europe entered the Neolithic era, and its inhabitants became sedentary.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] After demographic and agricultural development between the 4th and 3rd millennia BC, metallurgy appeared, initially working gold, copper and bronze, then later iron.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has numerous megalithic sites from the Neolithic, including the Carnac stones site (approximately 3,300 BC).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 600 BC, Ionian Greeks from Phocaea founded the colony of Massalia (present-day Marseille).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Celtic tribes penetrated parts of eastern and northern France, spreading through the rest of the country between the 5th and 3rd century BC.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Around 390 BC, the Gallic chieftain Brennus and his troops made their way to Roman Italy, defeated the Romans in the Battle of the Allia, and besieged and ransomed Rome.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This left Rome weakened, and the Gauls continued to harass the region until 345 BC, when they entered into a peace treaty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, the Romans and the Gauls remained adversaries for centuries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Around 125 BC, the south of Gaul was conquered by the Romans, who called this region *Provincia Nostra* ("Our Province"), which evolved into Provence in French.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Julius Caesar conquered the remainder of Gaul and overcame a revolt by Gallic chieftain Vercingetorix in 52 BC.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Gaul was divided by Augustus into provinces, and many cities were founded during the Gallo-Roman period, including Lugdunum (present-day Lyon), the capital of the Gauls.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 250–290 AD, Roman Gaul suffered a crisis with its fortified borders attacked by barbarians.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The situation improved in the first half of the 4th century, a period of revival and prosperity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 312, Emperor Constantine I converted to Christianity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Christian demographic, who had been persecuted, increased.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, the onset of the 5th century marked the resumption of major tribal migrations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Teutonic tribes invaded the region, the Visigoths settling in the southwest, the Burgundians along the Rhine Valley, and the Franks in the north.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In late antiquity, Gaul was divided into Germanic kingdoms and a remaining Gallo-Roman territory.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Celtic Britons, fleeing the Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain, settled in west Armorica; the Armorican peninsula was renamed Brittany, and Celtic culture was revived.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The first leader to unite all Franks was Clovis I, who began his reign as king of the Salian Franks in 481, routing the last forces of the Roman governors in 486.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Clovis said he would be baptised a Christian in the event of victory against the Visigothic Kingdom, which was said to have guaranteed the battle.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Clovis regained the southwest from the Visigoths and was baptised in 508.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Clovis was the first Germanic conqueror after the Fall of the Western Roman Empire to convert to Catholic Christianity; thus, France was given the title "Eldest daughter of the Church" by the papacy, and French kings were called "the Most Christian Kings of France".
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Franks embraced the Christian Gallo-Roman culture, and Gaul was renamed *Francia* ("Land of the Franks").
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Germanic Franks adopted Romanic languages.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Clovis made Paris his capital and established the Merovingian dynasty, but his kingdom would not survive his death.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Franks treated land as a private possession and divided it among their heirs, so four kingdoms emerged from that of Clovis: Paris, Orléans, Soissons, and Rheims.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The last Merovingian kings lost power to their mayors of the palace (head of household).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] One mayor of the palace, Charles Martel, defeated an Umayyad invasion at the Battle of Tours in 732.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] His son, Pepin the Short, seized the crown of Francia from the weakened Merovingians and founded the Carolingian dynasty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Pepin's son Charlemagne reunited the Frankish kingdoms and built an empire across Western and Central Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Proclaimed Holy Roman Emperor by Pope Leo III and thus establishing the French government's longtime historical association with the Catholic Church, Charlemagne tried to revive the Western Roman Empire and its cultural grandeur.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Charlemagne's son Louis I kept the empire united, althogugh it was divided between Louis' three sons into East Francia, Middle Francia and West Francia in 843.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] West Francia approximated the area occupied by modern France and was its precursor.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Throughout the 9th and 10th centuries, incessant Viking raids severely weakened the Carolingian monarchy, accelerating the fragmentation of West Francia into a decentralised, feudal society.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] As central authority faltered, local nobility secured hereditary rights to their titles and lands, creating a system where the king's authority became more religious and symbolic than secular, frequently challenged by powerful territorial princes.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] After the Battle of Hastings in 1066, William the Conqueror added "King of England" to his titles, becoming vassal and the equal of the king of France, creating recurring tensions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Carolingian dynasty ruled France until 987, when Hugh Capet was crowned king of the Franks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] His descendants unified the country through wars and inheritance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From 1190, the Capetian rulers began to be referred as "kings of France" rather than "kings of the Franks".
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Later kings expanded their directly possessed *domaine royal* to cover over half of modern France by the 15th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Royal authority became more assertive, centred on a hierarchically conceived society distinguishing nobility, clergy, and commoners.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The nobility played a prominent role in Crusades to restore Christian access to the Holy Land.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French knights made up most reinforcements in the 200 years of the Crusades, in such a fashion that the Arabs referred to crusaders as *Franj*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French Crusaders imported French into the Levant, making Old French the base of the *lingua franca* ("Frankish language") of the Crusader states.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Albigensian Crusade was launched in 1209 to eliminate the heretical Cathars in the southwest of modern-day France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From the 11th century, the House of Plantagenet, rulers of the County of Anjou, established its dominion over the surrounding provinces of Maine and Touraine, then built an "empire" from England to the Pyrenees, covering half of modern France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Tensions between France and the Plantagenet empire would last a hundred years, until Philip II of France conquered most of its continental possessions between 1202 and 1214 and defeated the Angevin coalition at the Battle of Bouvines, leaving only England and Aquitaine to the Plantagenets.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Following this victory, France became the most prosperous and powerful kingdom in Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Charles IV the Fair died without an heir in 1328.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The crown passed to Philip of Valois rather than Edward Plantagenet, who had become Edward III of England the previous year.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During the reign of Philip, the monarchy reached the height of its medieval power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Edward contested Philip's throne in 1337, beginning the intermittent Hundred Years' War between England and France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Boundaries changed, but landholdings inside France by English kings remained extensive for decades.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] With charismatic leaders such as Joan of Arc, French counterattacks won back most English continental territories.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was struck by the Black Death, from which half of the 17 million population died.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French Renaissance saw cultural development and standardisation of French, which became the official language of France and Europe's aristocracy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France became rivals of the House of Habsburg during the Italian Wars, which would dictate much of their later foreign policy until the mid-18th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French explorers claimed lands in the Americas, paving expansion of the French colonial empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The rise of Protestantism led France to a civil war known as the French Wars of Religion.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This forced Huguenots to flee to Protestant regions such as the British Isles and Switzerland.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The wars were ended by Henri IV's Edict of Nantes, which granted some freedom of religion to the Huguenots.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Spanish troops assisted the Catholics from 1589 to 1594 and invaded France in 1597.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Spain and France returned to all-out war between 1635 and 1659.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Franco-Spanish War cost France 300,000 casualties; total deaths on both sides were 200,000.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Under Louis XIII, Cardinal Richelieu promoted centralisation of the state and reinforced royal power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] He destroyed castles of defiant lords and denounced the use of private armies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] By the end of the 1620s, Richelieu established "the royal monopoly of force".
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France fought in the Thirty Years' War, supporting the Protestant side against the Habsburgs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From the 16th to the 19th century, France was responsible for about 10% of the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During Louis XIV's minority, trouble known as The Fronde occurred.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This rebellion was driven by feudal lords and sovereign courts as a reaction to the royal absolute power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The monarchy reached its peak during the 17th century and reign of Louis XIV, during which France further increased its influence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] By turning lords into courtiers at the Palace of Versailles, his command of the military went unchallenged.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] By the mid-17th century, France had emerged as the dominant power in Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Under the reign of Louis XIV, it built Europe's strongest army, fought a series of wars, and experienced remarkable artistic and scientific flourishing.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It also became the most populous European country and had tremendous influence over European politics, economy, and culture.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French became the most-used language in diplomacy, science, and literature until the 20th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France took control of territories in the Americas, Africa and Asia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1685, Louis XIV revoked the Edict of Nantes, forcing thousands of Huguenots into exile and published the *Code Noir* providing the legal framework for slavery and expelling Jews from French colonies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Under the wars of Louis XV, France lost New France and most Indian possessions after its defeat in the Seven Years' War (1756–1763).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its European territory kept growing, however, with acquisitions such as Lorraine and Corsica.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Louis XV's weak rule, including the decadence of his court, discredited the monarchy, which in part paved the way for the French Revolution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Louis XVI supported America with money, fleets and armies, helping them win independence from Great Britain.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France gained revenge but verged on bankruptcy—a factor that contributed to the Revolution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Some of the Enlightenment occurred in French intellectual circles, and scientific breakthroughs, such as the naming of oxygen and the first hot air balloon carrying passengers, were achieved by French scientists.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French explorers took part in the voyages of scientific exploration through maritime expeditions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Enlightenment philosophy, in which reason is advocated as the primary source of legitimacy, undermined the power of and support for the monarchy and was a factor in the Revolution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French Revolution was a period of political and societal change that began with the Estates General of 1789, and ended with the coup of 18 Brumaire in 1799 and the formation of the French Consulate.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Many of its ideas are fundamental principles of liberal democracy, while its values and institutions remain central to modern political discourse.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its causes were a combination of social, political and economic factors, which the *Ancien Régime* proved unable to manage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A financial crisis and social distress led in May 1789 to the convocation of the Estates General, which was converted into a National Assembly in June.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Storming of the Bastille on 14 July led to a series of radical measures by the Assembly, among them the abolition of feudalism, state control over the Catholic Church in France, and a declaration of rights.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The next three years were dominated by a struggle for political control, exacerbated by economic depression.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Military defeats following the outbreak of the French Revolutionary Wars in April 1792 resulted in the insurrection of 10 August 1792.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The monarchy was abolished and replaced by the French First Republic in September, while Louis XVI was executed in January 1793.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] After another revolt in June 1793, the constitution was suspended and power passed from the National Convention to the Committee of Public Safety.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] About 16,000 people were executed in a Reign of Terror, which ended in July 1794.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Weakened by external threats and internal opposition, the Republic was replaced in 1795 by the Directory.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1799, the Consulate seized power in a coup led by Napoleon.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Napoleon became First Consul in 1799 and later Emperor of the French Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Changing sets of European coalitions declared wars on Napoleon's empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] His armies conquered most of continental Europe with swift victories such as the Austerlitz and battles of Jena-Auerstadt.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Members of the Bonaparte family were appointed monarchs in some of the newly established kingdoms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] These victories led to the worldwide expansion of French revolutionary ideals and reforms, such as the metric system, Napoleonic Code and Declaration of the Rights of Man.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1812 Napoleon attacked Russia, reaching Moscow.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Thereafter his army disintegrated through supply problems, disease, Russian attacks, and finally winter.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] After this catastrophic campaign and the ensuing uprising of European monarchies against his rule, Napoleon was defeated.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] About a million Frenchmen died during the Napoleonic Wars, including 306,000 killed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] After his brief return from exile, Napoleon was finally defeated in 1815 at the Battle of Waterloo, and the Bourbon monarchy was restored with new constitutional limitations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The discredited Bourbon dynasty was overthrown by the July Revolution of 1830, which established the constitutional July Monarchy; French troops began the conquest of Algeria.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Unrest led to the French Revolution of 1848 and the end of the July Monarchy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The abolition of slavery and the introduction of male universal suffrage was re-enacted in 1848.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1852, president of the French Republic, Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte, Napoleon I's nephew, was proclaimed emperor of the Second Empire, as Napoleon III.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] He multiplied French interventions abroad, especially in Crimea, Mexico and Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Napoleon III was unseated following defeat in the Franco-Prussian War of 1870, and his regime was replaced by the Third Republic.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] By 1875, the French conquest of Algeria was complete, with approximately 825,000 Algerians killed from famine, disease, and violence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France suffered an estimated 10,000 killed and 35,000 wounded across all colonial campaigns.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A few thousand died in Mexico or Vietnam, but the vast majority perished in Algeria.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Disease claimed an even heavier toll; one estimate puts total French and Foreign Legion deaths from battle and disease for the entire 19th century at 110,000.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France had colonial possessions since the beginning of the 17th century, but in the 19th and 20th centuries its empire extended significantly and became the second-largest behind the British Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Including metropolitan France, the total area reached almost 13 million square kilometres in the 1920s and 1930s, 9% of the world's land.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Known as the *Belle Époque*, the turn of the century was characterised by optimism, regional peace, economic prosperity and technological, scientific and cultural innovations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1905, state secularism was officially established.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During World War I, France played a decisive role in defeating the Central Powers as part of the Triple Entente, while participating in the majority of the war's major battles fought on the Western Front.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A rich industrial area in the north was occupied.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France and the Allies emerged victorious against the Central Powers at tremendous human cost.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It left 1.4 million French soldiers dead, 4% of its population.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In addition, France suffered 4,266,000 wounded.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Interwar was marked by intense international tensions and social reforms introduced by the Popular Front government (e.g., annual leave, eight-hour workdays, women in government).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 1940, France was invaded and quickly defeated by Nazi Germany.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was divided into a German occupation zone in the north, an Italian occupation zone and an unoccupied territory, the rest of France, which consisted of southern France and the French empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Vichy government, an authoritarian regime collaborating with Germany, ruled the unoccupied territory.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Free France, the government-in-exile led by Charles de Gaulle, was set up in London.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From 1942 to 1944, about 160,000 French citizens, including around 75,000 Jews, were deported to death and concentration camps.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] On 6 June 1944, the Allies invaded Normandy, and in August they invaded Provence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Allies and French Resistance emerged victorious, and French sovereignty was restored with the Provisional Government of the French Republic (GPRF).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This interim government, established by de Gaulle, continued to wage war against Germany and to purge collaborators from office.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It made important reforms e.g. suffrage extended to women and the creation of a social security system.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A new constitution resulted in the Fourth Republic (1946–1958), which saw strong economic growth (*les Trente Glorieuses*).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was a founding member of NATO and attempted to regain control of French Indochina, but was defeated by the Viet Minh in 1954.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France faced another anti-colonialist conflict in Algeria, then part of France and home to over one million European settlers (Pied-Noir).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French systematically used torture and repression, including extrajudicial killings to keep control.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] This conflict nearly led to a coup and civil war.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During the May 1958 crisis, the weak Fourth Republic gave way to the Fifth Republic, which included a strengthened presidency.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The war concluded with the Évian Accords in 1962 which led to Algerian independence, at a high price: between half a million and one million deaths and over 2 million internally-displaced Algerians.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Around one million Pied-Noirs and Harkis fled from Algeria to France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] A vestige of the empire is the French overseas departments and territories.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During the Cold War, de Gaulle pursued a policy of "national independence" towards the Western and Eastern blocs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] He withdrew from NATO's military-integrated command (while remaining within the alliance), launched a nuclear development programme and made France the fourth nuclear power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] He restored cordial Franco-German relations to create a European counterweight between American and Soviet spheres of influence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, he opposed any development of a supranational Europe, favouring sovereign nations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The revolt of May 1968 had an enormous social impact; it was a watershed moment when a conservative moral ideal (religion, patriotism, respect for authority) shifted to a more liberal moral ideal (secularism, individualism, sexual revolution).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Although the revolt was a political failure (the Gaullist party emerged stronger than before) it announced a split between the French and de Gaulle, who resigned.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the post-Gaullist era, France remained one of the most developed economies in the world but faced crises that resulted in high unemployment rates and increasing public debt.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the late 20th and early 21st centuries, France has been at the forefront of the development of a supranational European Union, notably by signing the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, establishing the eurozone in 1999 and signing the Treaty of Lisbon in 2007.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has fully reintegrated into NATO and since participated in most NATO-sponsored wars.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since the 19th century, France has received many immigrants, often male foreign workers from European Catholic countries who generally returned home when not employed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During the 1970s France faced an economic crisis and allowed new immigrants (mostly from the Maghreb, in northwest Africa) to permanently settle in France with their families and acquire citizenship.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It resulted in hundreds of thousands of Muslims living in subsidised public housing and suffering from high unemployment rates.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The government had a policy of assimilation of immigrants, where they were expected to adhere to French values and norms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From the 2000s, France experienced continued immigration from Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In addition, Calais became a transit area for migrants.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Opération Chammal, France's military efforts to contain ISIS, killed over 1,000 ISIS troops between 2014 and 2015.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The vast majority of France's territory and population is situated in Western Europe and is called Metropolitan France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It is bordered by the North Sea in the north, the English Channel in the northwest, the Atlantic Ocean in the west and the Mediterranean Sea in the southeast.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its land borders consist of Belgium and Luxembourg in the northeast, Germany and Switzerland in the east, Italy and Monaco in the southeast, and Andorra and Spain in the south and southwest.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Except for the northeast, most of France's land borders are roughly delineated by natural boundaries and geographic features: to the south, the Pyrenees and the Alps; to the southeast, Jura Mountains; and to the east, the Rhine river.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Including Overseas France, it also borders Suriname and Brazil through French Guiana in South America, and the Netherlands through Saint Martin in the Caribbean.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Metropolitan France includes various coastal islands, of which the largest is Corsica.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Metropolitan France is situated mostly between latitudes 41° and 51° N, and longitudes 6° W and 10° E, on the western edge of Europe, and thus lies within the northern temperate zone.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its continental part covers about 1000 km from north to south and from east to west.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Metropolitan France covers 551,500 square kilometres (212,935 sq mi), the largest among European Union members.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France's total land area, with its overseas departments and territories (excluding Adélie Land), is 643,801 km2 (248,573 sq mi), 0.45% of the total land area on Earth.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France possesses a wide variety of landscapes, from coastal plains in the north and west to the mountain ranges of the Alps in the southeast, the Massif Central in the south-central and Pyrenees in the southwest.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] With numerous overseas departments and territories scattered across the planet, France possesses the second-largest exclusive economic zone (EEZ) in the world, covering 11,035,000 km2 (4,261,000 sq mi).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Its EEZ covers approximately 8% of the total surface of all the EEZs of the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Metropolitan France has a wide variety of topographic sets and natural landscapes.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] During the Hercynian uplift in the Paleozoic Era, the Armorican Massif, the Massif Central, the Morvan, the Vosges and Ardennes ranges and the island of Corsica were formed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] These massifs delineate several sedimentary basins such as the Aquitaine Basin in the southwest and the Paris Basin in the north.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Various routes of natural passage, such as the Rhône Valley, allow easy communication.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Alpine, Pyrenean and Jura Mountains are much younger and have less eroded forms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] At 4,810.45 metres (15,782 ft) above sea level, Mont Blanc in the Alps is the highest point in Western Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] 60% of municipalities are classified as having moderate seismic risk.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The coastlines offer contrasting landscapes: mountain ranges along the French Riviera, coastal cliffs such as the Côte d'Albâtre, and wide sandy plains in the Languedoc.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Corsica lies off the Mediterranean coast.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has an extensive river system consisting of the four major rivers: the Seine, the Loire, the Garonne, the Rhône and their tributaries, whose combined catchment includes over 62% of the metropolitan territory.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Rhône divides the Massif Central from the Alps and flows into the Mediterranean Sea at the Camargue.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Garonne meets the Dordogne just after Bordeaux, forming the Gironde estuary, the largest estuary in Western Europe which after approximately 100 kilometres (62 mi) empties into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Other water courses drain towards the Meuse and Rhine along the northeastern borders.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has 11,000,000 km2 (4,200,000 sq mi) of marine waters within three oceans under its jurisdiction, of which 97% are overseas.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] On June 28, 2019, in Vérargues, the temperature reached 46 °C, setting a temperature record in Metropolitan France since records began.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Climate change means that this kind of heatwave in France can be expected to occur 10 times more frequently than it would have done a century ago.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France was one of the first countries to create an environment ministry, in 1971.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France is ranked 19th by carbon dioxide emissions due to the country's heavy investment in nuclear power following the 1973 oil crisis, which now accounts for 75 per cent of its electricity production and results in less pollution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] According to the 2020 Environmental Performance Index conducted by Yale and Columbia, France was the fifth most environmentally conscious country in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Like all European Union state members, France agreed to cut carbon emissions by at least 20% of 1990 levels by 2020.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] As of 2009, carbon dioxide emissions per capita are lower than that of China.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The country was set to impose a carbon tax in 2009; however, the plan was abandoned due to fears of it burdening French businesses.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Forests account for 31 per cent of the land area—the fourth-highest proportion in Europe—representing an increase of 7 per cent since 1990.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The forests are some of the most diverse in Europe, comprising more than 140 species of trees.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 4.52/10, ranking it 123rd globally.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] There are nine national parks and 46 natural parks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France is a representative democracy organised as a unitary semi-presidential republic.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Democratic traditions and values are deeply rooted in French culture, identity and politics.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Constitution of the Fifth Republic was approved by referendum in 1958, establishing a framework consisting of executive, legislative and judicial branches.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It sought to address the instability of the Third and Fourth Republics by combining elements of both the parliamentary and presidential systems, while greatly strengthening the authority of the executive relative to the legislature.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The president, who is Emmanuel Macron since 2017, is the head of state, elected directly by universal adult suffrage for a five-year term.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The prime minister, who is Sébastien Lecornu since 2025, is the head of government, appointed by the president to lead the government.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The president has the power to dissolve parliament or circumvent it by submitting referendums directly to the people; the president also appoints judges and civil servants, negotiates and ratifies international agreements, and serves as commander-in-chief of the French Armed Forces.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The prime minister determines public policy and oversees the civil service, with an emphasis on domestic matters.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the 2022 presidential election, Macron was re-elected.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Two months later in the legislative elections, Macron lost his parliamentary majority and had to form a minority government.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The legislature consists of the French Parliament, a bicameral body made up of a lower house, the National Assembly, and an upper house, the Senate.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Legislators in the National Assembly, known as *députés*, represent local constituencies and are directly elected for five-year terms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Assembly has the power to dismiss the government by majority vote.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Senators are chosen by an electoral college for six-year terms, with half the seats submitted to election every three years.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Senate's legislative powers are limited; in the event of disagreement between the two chambers, the National Assembly has the final say.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The parliament is responsible for determining the rules and principles concerning most areas of law, political amnesty, and fiscal policy; however, the government may draft specific details concerning most laws.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In the 2017 presidential and legislative elections, the radical centrist party La République En Marche!
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] (LREM) became the dominant force, overtaking both Socialists and Republicans.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] LREM's opponent in the second round of the 2017 and 2022 presidential elections was the growing far-right party National Rally (RN).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since 2020, The Ecologists have performed well in mayoral elections in major cities while on a national level, the New Ecological and Social People's Union was the second-largest voting block elected to the lower house in 2022.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Right-wing populist RN became the largest opposition party in the National Assembly in 2022.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The electorate is constitutionally empowered to vote on amendments passed by the Parliament and bills submitted by the president.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Referendums have played a key role in shaping French politics and even foreign policy; voters have decided on such matters as Algeria's independence, the election of the president by popular vote, the formation of the EU, and the reduction of presidential term limits.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since 2016, France is divided into 18 administrative regions: 13 regions in metropolitan France (including Corsica), and five overseas.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The regions are further subdivided into 101 departments, which are numbered mainly alphabetically.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The department number is used in postal codes and was formerly used on vehicle registration plates.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Among the 101 French departments, five (French Guiana, Guadeloupe, Martinique, Mayotte, and Réunion) are in overseas regions that are simultaneously overseas departments, enjoying the same status as metropolitan departments and are thereby included in the European Union.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The 101 departments are subdivided into 335 arrondissements, which are, in turn, subdivided into 2,054 cantons.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] These cantons are divided into 36,658 communes, which are municipalities with an elected municipal council.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Three communes—Paris, Lyon and Marseille—are subdivided into 45 municipal arrondissements.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Overseas collectivities and territories form part of the French Republic but do not form part of the European Union or its fiscal area (except for Saint Barthélemy, which seceded from Guadeloupe in 2007).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Pacific Collectivities of French Polynesia, Wallis and Futuna, and New Caledonia continue to use the CFP franc whose value is strictly linked to the euro.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France is a founding member of the United Nations and serves as one of the permanent members of the UN Security Council with veto rights.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 2015 it was described as "the best networked state in the world" due to its membership in more international institutions than any other country; these include the G7, World Trade Organization, the Pacific Community and the Indian Ocean Commission.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It is an associate member of the Association of Caribbean States and a leading member of the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie of 84 French-speaking countries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] As a significant hub for international relations, France has the third-largest assembly of diplomatic missions, behind China and the United States.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It also hosts the headquarters of several international organisations, including the OECD, UNESCO, Interpol, the International Bureau of Weights and Measures, and the OIF.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French foreign policy after World War II has been largely shaped by membership in the European Union, of which it was a founding member.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since the 1963 Élysée Treaty, France has developed close ties with reunified Germany to become the most influential driving force of the EU.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since 1904 France has maintained an "Entente Cordiale" with the United Kingdom, and there has been a strengthening of ties between the countries, especially militarily.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France is a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), but under President Charles de Gaulle excluded itself from the joint military command in protest of the Special Relationship between the U.S. and UK, and to preserve the independence of French foreign and security policies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Under Nicolas Sarkozy, France rejoined the NATO joint military command.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France retains strong political and economic influence in its former African colonies (*Françafrique*) and has supplied economic aid and troops for peacekeeping missions in Ivory Coast and Chad.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] From 2012 to 2021, France and other African states intervened in support of the Malian government in the Mali War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 2017, France was the world's fourth-largest donor of development aid in absolute terms.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French Armed Forces (*Forces armées françaises*) are the military and paramilitary forces of France, under the president as commander-in-chief.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Together they are among the largest armed forces in the world and the largest in the EU.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] According to a 2015 study by Crédit Suisse, the French Armed Forces ranked as the world's sixth-most powerful military and the second most powerful in Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France's annual military expenditure in 2023 was US$61.3 billion, or 2.1% of its GDP, making it the eighth biggest military spender in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] There has been no national conscription since 1997.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has been a recognised nuclear state since 1960.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] It is a party to both the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The French nuclear force (formerly known as "*Force de Frappe*") consists of four *Triomphant*-class submarines equipped with submarine-launched ballistic missiles.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has major military industries and one of the largest aerospace sectors in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The country has produced such equipment as the Dassault Rafale fighter, the *Charles de Gaulle* aircraft carrier, the Exocet missile, and the Leclerc tank, among others.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France is a major arms seller, with most of its arsenal's designs available for the export market, except for nuclear-powered devices.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Weapons exported totalled 27 billion euros in 2022, up from 11.7 billion euros the previous year.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The UAE contributed more than 16 billion euros arms to the French total.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Among the largest French defence companies are Dassault, Thales and Safran.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Directorate General for External Security is a component of the Armed Forces under the authority of the Ministry of Defence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The General Directorate for Internal Security operates under the authority of the Ministry of the Interior.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France's cybersecurity capabilities are regularly ranked as some of the most robust of any nation in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France uses a civil legal system, wherein law arises primarily from written statutes; judges are not to make law, but merely to interpret it (though the amount of judicial interpretation in certain areas makes it equivalent to case law in a common law system).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Basic principles of the rule of law were laid in the Napoleonic Code (which was largely based on royal law codified under King Louis XIV).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In agreement with the principles of the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen, the law should only prohibit actions detrimental to society.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] French law is divided into two principal areas: private law and public law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Private law includes, in particular, civil law and criminal law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Public law includes, in particular, administrative law and constitutional law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, in practical terms, French law comprises three principal areas of law: civil law, criminal law, and administrative law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Criminal laws can only address the future and not the past (criminal *ex post facto* laws are prohibited).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] To be applicable, every law must be officially published in the *Journal officiel de la République française*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France does not recognise religious law as a motivation for the enactment of prohibitions; it has long abolished blasphemy laws and sodomy laws.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, "offences against public decency" or disturbing public order have been used to repress public expressions of homosexuality or street prostitution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France generally has a positive reputation regarding LGBTQ rights.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Since 1999, civil unions for homosexual couples have been permitted, and since 2013, same-sex marriage and LGBT adoption are legal.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] France has laws against racism and antisemitism, while the 1990 Gayssot Act prohibits Holocaust denial.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 2024, France became the first nation in the European Union to explicitly protect abortion in its constitution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Freedom of religion is constitutionally guaranteed by the 1789 Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The 1905 French law on the Separation of the Churches and the State is the basis for *laïcité* (state secularism): the state does not formally recognise any religion, except in Alsace-Moselle, which continues to subsidise education and clergy of Catholicism, Lutheranism, Calvinism, and Judaism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] Nonetheless, France does recognise religious associations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] The Parliament has listed many religious movements as dangerous cults since 1995 and has banned wearing conspicuous religious symbols in schools since 2004.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] In 2010, it banned the wearing of face-covering Islamic veils in public; human rights groups such as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch described the law as discriminatory towards Muslims.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p01] However, it is supported by most of the population.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has a social market economy characterised by sizeable government involvement and diversified sectors.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] For two centuries, it has consistently ranked among the ten largest globally; as of 2025 it is the world's ninth largest by purchasing power parity and second largest in the EU, after Germany.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Considered a great power with considerable economic strength, it is a member of the Group of Seven leading industrialised countries, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), and the G20.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France ranked 13th in the 2025 Global Innovation Index.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The economy is highly diversified; services represent two-thirds of both the workforce and GDP, while the industrial sector accounts for a fifth of GDP and a similar proportion of employment.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France is the third-biggest manufacturing country in Europe, behind Germany and Italy, and ranks eighth in the world by manufacturing output, at 1.9 per cent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Less than 2 per cent of GDP is generated by the primary sector, namely agriculture; the agricultural sector is among the largest in value and leads the EU in overall production.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2018 France was the fifth-largest trading nation and second-largest in Europe, with the value of exports representing over a fifth of GDP.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Its membership in the eurozone and the broader European single market facilitates access to capital, goods, services, and skilled labour.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Despite protectionist policies over certain industries, particularly in agriculture, France has generally played a leading role in fostering free trade and commercial integration in Europe to enhance its economy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2019, it ranked first in Europe and 13th in the world in foreign direct investment, with European countries and the United States being leading sources.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] According to the Bank of France (founded in 1800), the leading recipients of foreign direct investment are manufacturing, real estate, finance and insurance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Paris Region has the highest concentration of multinational firms in mainland Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Under the doctrine of *dirigisme*, the government historically played a major role in the economy; policies such as indicative planning and nationalisation are credited for contributing to three decades of unprecedented postwar economic growth known as *Trente Glorieuses*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] At its peak in 1982, the public sector accounted for one-fifth of industrial employment and over four-fifths of the credit market.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Beginning in the late 20th century, regulations and state involvement in the economy were loosened, with most leading companies becoming privately owned; state ownership still dominates transportation, defence and broadcasting.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Policies aimed at promoting economic dynamism and privatisation have improved France's economic standing globally: it is among the world's 10 most innovative countries in the 2020 Bloomberg Innovation Index, and the 15th most competitive according to the 2019 Global Competitiveness Report.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Paris stock exchange is one of the oldest in the world, created in 1724.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some examples of the most valuable French companies include LVMH, L'Oréal and Sociéte Générale.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has historically been one of the world's major agricultural centres and remains a "global agricultural powerhouse"; France is the world's sixth-biggest exporter of agricultural products, generating a trade surplus of over €7.4 billion.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Nicknamed "the granary of the old continent", over half its total land area is farmland, of which 45 per cent is devoted to permanent field crops such as cereals.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The country's diverse climate, extensive arable land, modern farming technology, and EU subsidies have made it Europe's leading agricultural producer and exporter.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] With 102 million international tourist arrivals in 2025, France is the world's top tourist destination and ranks third in tourism-derived income due to shorter visit durations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Disneyland Paris is Europe's most popular theme park, with 15 million combined visitors to the resort's Disneyland Park and Walt Disney Studios Park in 2009.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] With more than 10 million tourists per year, the French Riviera is the second leading tourist destination in the country, after the Paris Region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] With 6 million tourists per year, the castles of the Loire Valley (French: *châteaux*) and the Loire Valley are the third leading tourist destination.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has 54 sites inscribed on the UNESCO World Heritage List, ranking it fourth worldwide by number of sites.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France features cities of high cultural interest, beaches and seaside resorts, ski resorts, as well as rural regions that many enjoy for their beauty and tranquillity (green tourism).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Small and picturesque villages are promoted through the association *Les Plus Beaux Villages de France* (literally "The Most Beautiful Villages of France").
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The "Remarkable Gardens" label is a list of the over 200 gardens classified by the Ministry of Culture.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] This label is intended to protect and promote remarkable gardens and parks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France attracts many religious pilgrims on their way to St.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] James or to Lourdes, a town in the Hautes-Pyrénées that hosts several million visitors a year.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France is the world's tenth-largest producer of electricity. Électricité de France (EDF), which is majority-owned by the French government, is the country's main producer and distributor of electricity and one of the world's largest electric utility companies, ranking third in revenue globally.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2018, EDF produced roughly one-fifth of the EU's electricity, primarily from nuclear power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2021, France was the biggest energy exporter in Europe, mostly to the UK and Italy, and the largest net exporter of electricity in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Since the 1973 oil crisis, France has pursued a strong policy of energy security, namely through heavy investment in nuclear energy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is one of 32 countries with nuclear power plants, ranking second in the world by the number of operational nuclear reactors at 56.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Consequently, 70% of its electricity is generated by nuclear power, the highest proportion in the world by a wide margin; only Slovakia and Ukraine also derive a majority of electricity from nuclear power, at roughly 53% and 51%, respectively.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France is considered a world leader in nuclear technology, with reactors and fuel products being major exports.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The significant reliance on nuclear power has resulted in comparatively slower adoption of renewable energy relative to other Western nations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Nevertheless, between 2008 and 2019, its production capacity from renewable energies rose consistently and nearly doubled.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Hydropower is by far the leading source, accounting for over half of renewable energy sources and contributing 13% of its electricity the third highest proportion in Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Most hydroelectric plants, such as Eguzon, Étang de Soulcem, and Lac de Vouglans, are managed by EDF.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France aims to further expand hydropower into 2040.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The railway network in France stretches 29,473 kilometres (18,314 mi) as of 2008 and is the second most extensive in Western Europe after Germany's.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is operated by the SNCF, and high-speed trains include Thalys, Eurostar and TGV, which travels at 320 km/h (199 mph).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Eurostar and LeShuttle connect with the United Kingdom through the Channel Tunnel.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Rail connections exist to all other neighbouring countries in Europe except Andorra.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Intra-urban connections are also well developed, with most major cities having underground or tramway services complementing bus services.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are approximately 1,027,183 kilometres (638,262 mi) of serviceable roadway, ranking it the most extensive network of the European continent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Paris Region is enveloped with a dense network of roads and highways, which connect it with virtually all parts of the country.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Roads also handle substantial international traffic, connecting with cities in neighbouring countries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There is no annual registration fee or road tax; usage of the mostly privately owned motorways is through tolls except in the vicinity of large communes.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The new car market is dominated by domestic brands such as Renault, Peugeot and Citroën.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France possesses the Millau Viaduct, the world's tallest bridge, and has built many important bridges such as the Pont de Normandie.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Diesel and petrol-driven cars and lorries cause a large part of the country's air pollution and greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Charles de Gaulle Airport, located in the vicinity of Paris, is the largest and busiest airport in the country, handling the vast majority of popular and commercial traffic and connecting Paris with virtually all major cities across the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Air France is the national carrier airline, although numerous private airline companies provide domestic and international travel services.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are ten major ports, the largest of which is in Marseille, which also is the largest bordering the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] 12,261 kilometres (7,619 mi) of waterways traverse France including the Canal du Midi, which connects the Mediterranean Sea to the Atlantic Ocean through the Garonne river.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] With an estimated population of 69,081,996 people, France is the 20th most populous country in the world, the third-most populous in Europe, and the second most populous in the European Union.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] For much of the 21st century, France has been an outlier among developed countries, particularly in Europe, for its relatively high rate of natural population growth; by birth rates alone, it was responsible for almost all natural population growth in the EU in 2006.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Between 2006 and 2016, France saw the second-highest overall increase in population in the EU and was one of four EU countries where natural births accounted for the most population growth.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] This was the highest rate since the end of the baby boom in 1973 and coincides with the rise in the total fertility rate from a nadir of 1.7 in 1994 to 2.0 in 2010.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Since 2011, the fertility rate has been steadily declining; it stood at 1.79 per woman in 2023, below the replacement rate of 2.1 and well below the high of 4.41 in 1800.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Fertility rate and crude birth rate nonetheless remain the highest in the EU and among the highest in Europe overall, where the average is 1.5.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The mean age of French women at the birth of their first child was 29.1, slightly younger than the EU average of 29.7.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Like many developed nations, the population is aging: The average age is 41.7 years, while roughly one-fifth of French people are 65 or over.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is projected that one in three French will be over 60 by 2024.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Life expectancy at birth is 82.7 years, the 12th highest in the world; French Polynesia and Réunion ranked fourth and 11th in life expectancy, at 84.07 years and 83.55, respectively.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] From 2006 to 2011, population growth averaged 0.6 percent per year; since 2011, annual growth has been between 0.4 and 0.5 percent annually, and France is projected to continue growing until 2044.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Immigrants are major contributors to this trend; in 2010, roughly one in four newborns (27 percent) in Metropolitan France had at least one foreign-born parent, and another 24 percent had at least one parent born outside Europe (excluding French overseas territories).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2021, the share of children of foreign-born mothers was 23 percent.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The fertility rate in France dropped to 1.56 in 2025.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] This was the lowest rate since the end of the first world war.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] (Note: since its 2020 revision of metropolitan area borders, INSEE considers that Nice is a metropolitan area separate from the Cannes-Antibes metropolitan area; these two combined would have a population of 1,045,839, as of the 2023 census).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Rural flight was a perennial political issue throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Historically, French people were mainly of Celtic-Gallic origin, with a significant admixture of Italic (Romans) and Germanic (Franks) groups reflecting centuries of respective migration and settlement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Through the course of the Middle Ages, France incorporated various neighbouring ethnic and linguistic groups, as evidenced by Breton elements in the west, Aquitanian in the southwest, Scandinavian in the northwest, Alemannic in the northeast, and Ligurian in the southeast.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2004 the *Institut Montaigne* estimated that within Metropolitan France, 51 million people were white (85% of the population), 6 million were northwest African (10%), 2 million were black (3.3%), and 1 million were Asian (1.7%).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are also sizeable minorities of other European ethnic groups, namely Spanish, Portuguese, Polish, and Greek.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has a significant Gitan (Romani) population, numbering between 20,000 and 400,000; many foreign Roma are expelled back to Bulgaria and Romania frequently.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is estimated that 40% of the French population is descended at least partially from the different waves of immigration since the early 20th century; between 1921 and 1935 alone, about 1.1 million net immigrants came to France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The next largest wave came in the 1960s when around 1.6 million *pieds-noirs* returned to France following the independence of its northwest African possessions of Algeria and Morocco.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] They were joined by numerous former colonial subjects from North and West Africa, as well as numerous European immigrants from Spain and Portugal.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France remains a major destination for immigrants, accepting about 200,000 legal immigrants annually.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2005, it was Western Europe's leading recipient of asylum seekers, with an estimated 50,000 applications (albeit a 15% decrease from 2004).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2010, France received about 48,100 asylum applications—placing it among the top five asylum recipients in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In subsequent years it saw the number of applications increase, ultimately doubling to 100,412 in 2017.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The European Union allows free movement between the member states, although France established controls to curb Eastern European migration.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Foreigners' rights are established in the Code of Entry and Residence of Foreigners and of the Right to Asylum.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Immigration remains a contentious political issue.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2008 INSEE estimated that the number of foreign-born immigrants was around 5 million (8% of the population), while their French-born descendants numbered 6.5 million, or 11% of the population.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Thus, nearly a fifth of the country's population were either first or second-generation immigrants, of which more than 5 million were of European origin and 4 million of Maghrebi ancestry.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2008, France granted citizenship to 137,000 persons, mostly from Morocco, Algeria and Turkey.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2022, more than 320,000 migrants came to France, with the majority coming from Africa.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2014, the INSEE reported a significant increase in the number of immigrants coming from Spain, Portugal and Italy between 2009 and 2012.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] According to the institute, this increase resulted from the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Statistics on Spanish immigrants in France show a growth of 107 per cent between 2009 and 2012, with the population growing from 5,300 to 11,000.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Of the total of 229,000 foreigners coming to France in 2012, nearly 8% were Portuguese, 5% British, 5% Spanish, 4% Italian, 4% German, 3% Romanian, and 3% Belgian.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The official language is French, a Romance language derived from Latin.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Since 1635, the Académie Française has been the official authority on the French language, although its recommendations carry no legal weight.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are also regional languages spoken in France, such as Occitan, Breton, Catalan, Flemish (Dutch dialect), Alsatian (German dialect), Basque, and Corsican (Italian dialect).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Italian was the official language of Corsica up to 1859.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Although regional languages do not have the status of official languages, they are recognised by Article 75-1 of the constitution as part of France's heritage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The government does not regulate the choice of language in publications by individuals, but the use of French is required by law in commercial and workplace communications.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French government tries to promote French in the EU and globally through institutions such as the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are 77 vernacular minority languages, eight spoken in Metropolitan France and 69 in the overseas territories.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France is a secular country in which freedom of religion is a constitutional right.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Alsace and Moselle, which were part of the German Empire when state secularism was established in France, is an exception since the local law stipulates official status and state funding for Lutheranism, Catholicism, and Judaism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Catholicism has been the main religion in France for more than a millennium, and it was once the state religion.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Its role nowadays has been greatly reduced; nevertheless in 2012, among the 47,000 religious buildings in France, 94% were Catholic churches.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The government is prohibited from recognising specific rights to any religious community (with the exception of legacy statutes like those of military chaplains and the aforementioned local law in Alsace-Moselle).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It recognises religious organisations according to formal legal criteria that do not address religious doctrine, and religious organisations are expected to refrain from intervening in policymaking.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some religious groups, such as scientology, the Children of God, the Unification Church, and the Order of the Solar Temple, are considered cults (*sectes* in French) and are not granted the same status as recognised religions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French health care system is one of universal health care largely financed by government national health insurance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In its 2000 assessment of world health care systems, the World Health Organization (WHO) found that France provided the "close to best overall health care" in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French health care system was ranked first worldwide by the WHO in 1997.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2011, France spent 11.6% of its GDP on health care, or US$4,086 per capita, a figure much higher than the average spent by countries in Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Approximately 77% of health expenditures are covered by government-funded agencies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Care is generally free for people affected by chronic diseases such as cancer, AIDS or cystic fibrosis.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The life expectancy at birth is 80 years for men and 85.6 years for women.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] There are 3.2 physicians for every 1000 inhabitants, 5.7 hospital beds for every 1000 inhabitants, and average health care spending per capita was US$8,630 in 2022, representing 12.1% of GDP.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] As of 2007, approximately 140,000 inhabitants (0.4%) are living with HIV/AIDS.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 1802, Napoleon created the lycée, the second and final stage of secondary education that prepares students for higher education studies or a profession.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Jules Ferry is considered the father of the French modern school, leading reforms in the late 19th century that established free, secular and compulsory education (currently mandatory to age 16).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French education is centralised and divided into three stages: primary, secondary, and higher education.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Programme for International Student Assessment, coordinated by the OECD, ranked France's education as near the OECD average in 2018.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] School children in France reported greater concern about the disciplinary climate and behaviour in classrooms compared to other OECD countries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The *Grandes écoles* have been criticised for alleged elitism, producing many if not most of France's high-ranking civil servants, CEOs and politicians.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France also supports a network of schools internationally through the Agency for French Education Abroad.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The network includes a mix of directly managed schools, subsidized institutions, and partner schools, and provides French education to students around the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The origins of a distinctly French art date back to the Middle Ages.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the 12th century, Paris and its region saw the birth of Gothic art, known at the time as *Opus Francigenum* (lit.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] 'French work'), which from the cathedrals of Chartres, Amiens and Reims soon radiated throughout Europe, thanks to French architects and sculptors who went abroad.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French art was very much influenced first by Flemish art then by Italian art at the time of the Renaissance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Jean Fouquet, the most famous medieval French painter, is said to have been the first to travel to Italy and experience the Early Renaissance firsthand.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Renaissance painting School of Fontainebleau was directly inspired by Italian painters such as Primaticcio and Rosso Fiorentino, who both worked in France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Two of the most famous French artists of the time of the Baroque era, Nicolas Poussin and Claude Lorrain, lived in Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French artists developed the rococo style in the early 18th century, as a more intimate evolution of the Baroque style, the works of the court-endorsed artists Antoine Watteau, François Boucher and Jean-Honoré Fragonard being the most representative in the country.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French Revolution brought great changes, as Napoleon favoured artists of neoclassic style such as Jacques-Louis David and the highly influential Académie des Beaux-Arts defined the style known as Academism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the second part of the 19th century, France's influence over painting grew, with the development of new styles of painting such as Impressionism and Symbolism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The most famous impressionist painters of the period were Camille Pissarro, Édouard Manet, Edgar Degas, Claude Monet and Auguste Renoir.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The second generation of impressionist-style painters, Paul Cézanne, Paul Gauguin, Toulouse-Lautrec and Georges Seurat, were also at the avant-garde of artistic evolutions, as well as the fauvist artists Henri Matisse, André Derain and Maurice de Vlaminck.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Cubism was developed by Georges Braque and the Spanish painter Pablo Picasso, who was living in Paris.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Other foreign artists also settled and worked in or near Paris, such as Vincent van Gogh and Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the early 20th century and in particular during the interwar period, a loose collection of foreign artists of whom many were Jewish formed the School of Paris.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Amongst these artists were Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Yitzhak Frenel, Jules Pascin and others.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Second World War led to the deaths or exile of multiple artists, resulting in the relative fall of Paris' domination and centrality in the world art scene in favour of New York City.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] During the Middle Ages, many fortified castles were built by feudal nobles to mark their powers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some French castles that survive are Chinon, Château d'Angers, Château de Vincennes and the Cathar castles.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] During this era, France had been using Romanesque architecture like most of Western Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Gothic architecture, originally named *Opus Francigenum* meaning "French work", was born in Île-de-France and was the first French style of architecture to be imitated throughout Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Northern France is the home of some of the most important Gothic cathedrals and basilicas, the first of these being the Saint Denis Basilica (used as the royal necropolis); other important French Gothic cathedrals are Notre-Dame de Chartres and Notre-Dame d'Amiens.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The kings were crowned in another important Gothic church: Notre-Dame de Reims.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The final victory in the Hundred Years' War marked an important stage in the evolution of French architecture.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It was the time of the French Renaissance and several artists from Italy were invited to the French court; many residential palaces were built in the Loire Valley, from 1450 as a first reference the Château de Montsoreau.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Examples of such residential castles include the Château de Chambord, the Château de Chenonceau, or the Château d'Amboise.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Following the Renaissance and the end of the Middle Ages, Baroque architecture replaced the traditional Gothic style.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Baroque architecture found greater success in the secular domain than in the religious one.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the secular domain, the Palace of Versailles has many Baroque features.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Jules Hardouin-Mansart, who designed the extensions to Versailles, was one of the most influential French architects of the Baroque era; he is famous for his dome at Les Invalides.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some of the most impressive provincial Baroque architecture is found in places that were not yet French such as Place Stanislas in Nancy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] On the military architectural side, Vauban designed some of the most efficient fortresses in Europe and became an influential military architect; as a result, imitations of his works can be found all over Europe, the Americas, Russia and Turkey.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] After the Revolution, the Republicans favoured Neoclassicism although it was introduced in France before the revolution with such buildings as the Parisian Pantheon or the Capitole de Toulouse.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Built during the French First Empire, the Arc de Triomphe and Sainte Marie-Madeleine represent the best example of Empire style architecture.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Under Napoleon III, a wave of urbanism and architecture was given birth; extravagant buildings such as the neo-Baroque Palais Garnier were built.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The urban planning of the time was very organised and rigorous; most notably, Haussmann's renovation of Paris.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The architecture associated with this era is named Second Empire in English, the term being taken from the Second French Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] At this time there was a strong Gothic resurgence across Europe and in France; the associated architect was Eugène Viollet-le-Duc.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the late 19th century, Gustave Eiffel designed many bridges, such as the Garabit viaduct, and remains one of the most influential bridge designers of his time, although he is best remembered for the Eiffel Tower.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the 20th century, French-Swiss architect Le Corbusier designed several buildings in France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] More recently, French architects have combined both modern and old architectural styles.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Louvre Pyramid is an example of modern architecture added to an older building.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The most difficult buildings to integrate within French cities are skyscrapers, as they are visible from afar.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] For instance, in Paris since 1977, new buildings had to be under 37 metres (121 ft).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] A significant number of skyscrapers are located in the La Défense financial district.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Other massive buildings that are a challenge to integrate into their environment are large bridges; an example of the way this has been done is the Millau Viaduct.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some famous modern French architects include Jean Nouvel, Dominique Perrault, Christian de Portzamparc and Paul Andreu.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The earliest French literature dates from the Middle Ages, when there were several languages and dialects, and writers used their own spelling and grammar.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some authors of medieval texts, such as *Tristan and Iseult* and *Lancelot-Grail,* are unknown.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Three famous medieval authors are Chrétien de Troyes, Christine de Pizan (langue d'oïl), and Duke William IX of Aquitaine (langue d'oc).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Much medieval French poetry and literature was inspired by the legends of the Carolingian cycle, such as the *Song of Roland* and the chansons de geste.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The *Roman de Renart*, written in 1175 by Perrout de Saint Cloude, tells the story of the medieval character Reynard ('the Fox') and is another example of early French writing.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] An important 16th-century writer was François Rabelais, who wrote five popular early picaresque novels.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Rabelais was also in regular communication with Marguerite de Navarre, author of the *Heptaméron*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Michel de Montaigne's most famous work, *Essais*, started a literary genre.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French literature and poetry flourished during the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Denis Diderot is best known as the main editor of the *Encyclopédie*, whose aim was to sum up all the knowledge of his century and to fight ignorance and obscurantism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Charles Perrault was a prolific writer of children's fairy tales including *Puss in Boots*, *Cinderella*, *Sleeping Beauty* and *Bluebeard*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] At the start of the 19th century, symbolist poetry was an important movement, with poets such as Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine and Stéphane Mallarmé.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Victor Hugo is sometimes seen as "the greatest French writer of all time" for excelling in all literary genres.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Hugo's verse has been compared to that of Shakespeare, Dante and Homer.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] His novel *Les Misérables* is widely seen as one of the greatest novels ever written, and *The Hunchback of Notre Dame* has remained immensely popular.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the early 20th century France was a haven for literary freedom.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Works banned for obscenity in the US, the UK and other Anglophone nations were published in France decades before they were available in the respective authors' home countries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French were disinclined to punish literary figures for their writing, and prosecutions were rare.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Important writers of the 20th century include Marcel Proust, Louis-Ferdinand Céline, Jean Cocteau, Albert Camus, and Jean-Paul Sartre.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Antoine de Saint-Exupéry wrote *The Little Prince*, which is one of the best selling books in history.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Medieval French philosophy was dominated by Scholasticism until the emergence of Humanism in the Renaissance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Modern philosophy began in the 17th century with René Descartes, Blaise Pascal and Nicolas Malebranche.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Descartes was the first Western philosopher since ancient times to attempt to build a philosophical system from the ground up rather than building on the work of predecessors.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Major philosophical contributions in the 18th century included Voltaire, who came to embody the Enlightenment, and Jean-Jacques Rousseau, whose work highly influenced the French Revolution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French philosophers made major contributions to the field in the 20th century including the existentialist works of Simone de Beauvoir, Camus, and Sartre.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Other influential contributors include the moral and political works of Simone Weil, contributions to structuralism including from Claude Lévi-Strauss and the post-structuralist works by Michel Foucault.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French music experienced a golden age in the 17th century thanks to Louis XIV, who employed talented musicians and composers in the royal court.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Composers of this period include Marc-Antoine Charpentier, François Couperin, Michel-Richard Delalande, Jean-Baptiste Lully and Marin Marais, all of them composers at the court.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] After the death of Louis XIV, French musical creation lost dynamism, but in the next century the music of Jean-Philippe Rameau achieved some prestige.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Rameau became the dominant composer of French opera and the leading French composer of the harpsichord.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the field of classical music, France has produced notable composers such as Gabriel Fauré, Claude Debussy, Maurice Ravel, and Hector Berlioz.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Debussy and Ravel are the most prominent figures associated with Impressionist music.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The two composers invented new musical forms and new sounds.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Debussy was among the most influential composers of the late 19th and early 20th centuries, and his use of non-traditional scales and chromaticism influenced many composers who followed.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] His music is noted for its sensory content and frequent usage of atonality.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Erik Satie was a key member of the early-20th-century Parisian avant-garde.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Francis Poulenc's best-known works are his piano suite *Trois mouvements perpétuels* (1919), the ballet *Les Biches* (1923), the *Concert champêtre* (1928) for harpsichord and orchestra, the opera *Dialogues des Carmélites* (1957) and the *Gloria* (1959) for soprano, choir and orchestra.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the middle of the 20th century, Maurice Ohana, Pierre Schaeffer and Pierre Boulez contributed to the evolution of contemporary classical music.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French music then followed the rapid emergence of pop and rock music in the middle of the 20th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Although English-speaking creations achieved popularity in the country, French pop music, known as *chanson française*, has also remained very popular.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Among the most important French artists of the century are Édith Piaf, Georges Brassens, Léo Ferré, Charles Aznavour and Serge Gainsbourg.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Modern pop music has seen the rise of popular French hip hop, French rock, techno/funk, and turntablists/DJs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Although there are very few rock bands in France compared to English-speaking countries, bands such as Noir Désir, Mano Negra, Niagara, Les Rita Mitsouko and more recently Superbus, Phoenix and Gojira, or Shaka Ponk, have reached worldwide popularity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has historical and strong links with cinema, with two Frenchmen, Auguste and Louis Lumière (known as the Lumière Brothers) credited with creating cinema in 1895.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The world's first female filmmaker, Alice Guy-Blaché, was also from France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Several important cinematic movements, including the late 1950s and 1960s Nouvelle Vague, began in the country.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is noted for having a strong film industry, due in part to protections afforded by the government.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France remains a leader in filmmaking, as of 2015 producing more films than any other European country.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The nation also hosts the Cannes Festival, one of the most important and famous film festivals in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Apart from its strong and innovative film tradition, France has also been a gathering spot for artists from across Europe and the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] For this reason, French cinema is sometimes intertwined with the cinema of foreign nations.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Directors from nations such as Poland (Roman Polanski, Krzysztof Kieślowski, Andrzej Żuławski), Argentina (Gaspar Noé, Edgardo Cozarinsky), Russia (Alexandre Alexeieff, Anatole Litvak), Austria (Michael Haneke) and Georgia (Géla Babluani, Otar Iosseliani) are prominent in the ranks of French cinema.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Conversely, French directors have had prolific and influential careers in other countries, such as Luc Besson, Jacques Tourneur or Francis Veber in the United States.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Although the French film market is dominated by Hollywood, France is the only nation in the world where American films make up the smallest share of total film revenues, at 50%, compared with 77% in Germany and 69% in Japan.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French films account for 35% of the total film revenues of France, which is the highest percentage of national film revenues in the developed world outside the United States, compared to 14% in Spain and 8% in the UK.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2013, France was the second-largest exporter of films in the world, after the United States.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] As part of its advocacy of cultural exception, a political concept of treating culture differently from other commercial products, France succeeded in convincing all EU members to refuse to include culture and audiovisuals in the list of liberalised sectors of the WTO in 1993.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] This decision was confirmed in a vote by UNESCO in 2005.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Fashion has been an important industry and cultural export of France since the 17th century, and modern "haute couture" originated in Paris in the 1860s.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Today, Paris, along with London, Milan, and New York City, is considered one of the world's fashion capitals, and the city is home or headquarters to many of the premier fashion houses.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The expression Haute couture is, in France, a legally protected name, guaranteeing certain quality standards.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The association of France with fashion and style (French: *la mode*) dates largely to the reign of Louis XIV.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France renewed its dominance of the high fashion (French: *couture or haute couture*) industry in the years 1860–1960 through the establishment of the great couturier houses such as Chanel, Dior, and Givenchy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French perfume industry is the world leader in its sector and is centred on the town of Grasse.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] According to 2017 data compiled by Deloitte, Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessey (LVMH), a French brand, is the largest luxury company in the world by sales, selling more than twice the amount of its nearest competitor.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Moreover, France also possesses 3 of the top 10 luxury goods companies by sales (LVMH, Kering SA, L'Oréal), more than any other country in the world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2021, regional daily newspapers, such as *Ouest-France*, *Sud Ouest*, *La Voix du Nord*, *Dauphiné Libéré*, *Le Télégramme*, and *Le Progrès*, more than doubled the sales of national newspapers, such as *Le Monde*, *Le Figaro*, *L'Équipe* (sports), *Le Parisien*, and *Les Echos* (finance).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Free dailies, distributed in metropolitan centres, continue to increase their market share.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The sector of weekly magazines includes more than 400 specialised weekly magazines published in the country.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Influential weeklies also include investigative and satirical papers *Le Canard Enchaîné* and *Charlie Hebdo*, as well as *Paris Match*.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] As in most industrialised nations, the print media have been affected by a severe crisis with the rise of the internet.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 2008, the government launched a major initiative to help the sector reform and become financially independent, but in 2009 it had to give €600,000 to help the print media cope with the 2008 financial crisis, in addition to existing subsidies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In 1974, after years of centralised monopoly on radio and television, the governmental agency ORTF was split into several national institutions, but the three already-existing TV channels and four national radio stations remained under state control.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It was only in 1981 that the government allowed free broadcasting in the territory.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Some consider hate speech laws in France to be too broad or severe, undermining freedom of speech.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Different regions have different styles.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In the north, butter and cream are common ingredients, whereas olive oil is more commonly used in the south.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Each region of France has traditional specialties: cassoulet in the southwest, choucroute in Alsace, quiche in the Lorraine region, beef bourguignon in Burgundy, Provençal tapenade, etc.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France is most famous for its wines and cheeses, which are often named for the territory where they are produced (AOC).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] A meal typically consists of three courses, *entrée* ('starter'), *plat principal* ('main course'), and *fromage* ('cheese') or *dessert*, sometimes with a salad served before the cheese or dessert.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French cuisine is also regarded as a key element of the quality of life and the attractiveness of France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] A French publication, the *Michelin Guide*, awards *Michelin stars* for excellence to a select few establishments.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The acquisition or loss of a star can have dramatic effects on the success of a restaurant.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] By 2006, the *Michelin Guide* had awarded 620 stars to French restaurants.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] In addition to its wine tradition, France is also a major producer of beer and rum.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The three main French brewing regions are Alsace (60% of national production), Nord-Pas-de-Calais, and Lorraine.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French rum is made in distilleries on islands in the Atlantic and Indian oceans.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France hosts "the world's biggest annual sporting event", the annual cycling race Tour de France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Other popular sports played in France include football, judo, tennis, rugby union and pétanque.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has hosted events such as the 1938 and 1998 FIFA World Cups, the 2007 Rugby World Cup, and the 2023 Rugby World Cup.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The country also hosted the 1960 European Nations' Cup, UEFA Euro 1984, UEFA Euro 2016 and 2019 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The Stade de France in Saint-Denis is France's largest stadium and was the venue for the 1998 FIFA World Cup and 2007 Rugby World Cup finals.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Since 1923, France is famous for its 24 Hours of Le Mans sports car endurance race.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Several major tennis tournaments take place in France, including the Paris Masters and the French Open, one of the four Grand Slam tournaments.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] French martial arts include Savate and Fencing.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France has a close association with the Modern Olympic Games; it was a French aristocrat, Baron Pierre de Coubertin, who suggested the Games' revival, at the end of the 19th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Paris hosted the second Games in 1900, and has hosted the Olympics on five further occasions: the 1924 Summer Olympics, the 2024 Summer Olympics both in Paris and three Winter Games (1924 in Chamonix, 1968 in Grenoble and 1992 in Albertville).
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] France introduced Olympics for deaf people (Deaflympics) in 1924.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Both the national football team and the national rugby union team are nicknamed "*Les Bleus*".
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Football is the most popular sport in France, with over 1,800,000 registered players and over 18,000 registered clubs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] Rugby union is popular, particularly in Paris and the southwest of France.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The national rugby union team has competed at every Rugby World Cup; it takes part in the annual Six Nations Championship.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] The French Open, also called Roland-Garros, is a major tennis tournament held over two weeks between late May and early June at the Stade Roland-Garros in Paris.
[src:community-of-the-ark/france-p02] It is the premier clay court tennis championship event in the world and the second of four annual Grand Slam tournaments.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The history of Italy goes back to numerous Italic peoples, notably including the ancient Romans, who conquered the Mediterranean world during the Roman Republic and ruled it for centuries during the Roman Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] With the spread of Christianity, Rome became the seat of the Catholic Church and the Papacy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Barbarian invasions and other factors led to the decline and fall of the Western Roman Empire between late antiquity and the Early Middle Ages.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] By the 11th century, Italian city-states and maritime republics expanded, bringing renewed prosperity through commerce and laying the groundwork for modern capitalism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Italian Renaissance flourished during the 15th and 16th centuries and spread to the rest of Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Italian explorers discovered new routes to the Far East and the New World, contributing significantly to the Age of Discovery.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] After centuries of political and territorial divisions, the Kingdom of Italy was established in 1861, following wars of independence and the Expedition of the Thousand.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] From the late 19th to the early 20th century, Italy industrialised and acquired a colonial empire, while the south remained largely impoverished, fuelling a large immigrant diaspora to the Americas.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] From 1915 to 1918, Italy took part in World War I with the Entente against the Central Powers.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1922, the Italian fascist dictatorship was established.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During World War II, Italy was first part of the Axis until an armistice with the Allied powers (1940–1943), then a co-belligerent of the Allies during the Italian resistance and liberation of Italy from German occupation and the collaborationist RSI (1943–1945).
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1946, the monarchy was replaced by a republic and the country made a strong recovery.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] A developed country with an advanced economy, Italy has the eighth-largest nominal GDP in the world, the second-largest manufacturing sector in Europe, and plays a significant role in regional and – to a lesser extent – global economic, military, cultural, and political affairs.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] It is a founding and leading member of the European Union, and is part of numerous other international organisations and forums.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] As a cultural superpower, Italy has long been a renowned global centre of art, music, literature, cuisine, fashion, science and technology, and the source of multiple inventions and discoveries.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] It has the highest number of World Heritage Sites (61) and is the fourth most visited country in the world by international tourist arrivals.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Hypotheses for the etymology of *Italia* are numerous.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] One theory suggests it originated from an Ancient Greek term for the land of the *Italói*, a tribe that resided in the region now known as Calabria.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Originally thought to be named *Vituli*, some scholars suggest their totemic animal to be the calf (Latin: *vitulus*; Umbrian: *vitlo*; Oscan: *Víteliú*).
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Several ancient authors said it was named after a local ruler Italus.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The ancient Greek term for Italy initially referred only to the south of the Bruttium peninsula and parts of Catanzaro and Vibo Valentia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The larger concept of Oenotria and "Italy" became synonymous, and the name applied to most of Lucania as well.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Before the Roman Republic's expansion, the name was used by Greeks for the land between the strait of Messina and the line connecting the gulfs of Salerno and Taranto, corresponding to Calabria.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Greeks came to apply "Italia" to a larger region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In addition to the "Greek Italy" in the south, historians have suggested the existence of an "Etruscan Italy", which consisted of areas of central Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The borders of Roman Italy, *Italia*, are better established.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Cato's *Origines* describes Italy as the entire peninsula south of the Alps.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 264 BC, Roman Italy extended from the Arno and Rubicon rivers of the centre-north to the entire south.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The northern area, Cisalpine Gaul, considered geographically part of Italy, was occupied by Rome in the 220s BC, but remained politically separated.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] It was legally merged into the administrative unit of Italy in 42 BC.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Sardinia, Corsica, Sicily, and Malta were added to Italy by Diocletian in 292 AD, which made late-ancient Italy coterminous with the modern Italian geographical region.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Latin *Italicus* was used to describe "a man of Italy" as opposed to a *provincial*, or one from the Roman province.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The adjective *italianus*, from which *Italian* was derived, is from medieval Latin and was used alternatively with *Italicus* during the early modern period.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy was created.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] After the Lombard invasions, *Italia* was retained as the name for their kingdom, and its successor kingdom within the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Lower Paleolithic artefacts, dating back 850,000 years, have been recovered from Monte Poggiolo.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Excavations throughout Italy revealed a Neanderthal presence in the Middle Palaeolithic period 200,000 years ago, while modern humans appeared about 40,000 years ago at Riparo Mochi.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The ancient peoples of pre-Roman Italy were Indo-European, specifically the Italic peoples.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The main historic peoples of possible non-Indo-European or pre-Indo-European heritage include the Etruscans, the Elymians and Sicani of Sicily, and the prehistoric Sardinians, who gave birth to the Nuragic civilisation.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Other ancient populations include the Rhaetian people and Camunni, known for their rock drawings in Valcamonica.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] A natural mummy, Ötzi, dated 3400–3100 BC, was discovered in the Similaun glacier in 1991.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The first colonisers were the Phoenicians, who established emporiums on the coasts of Sicily and Sardinia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Some became small urban centres and developed parallel to Greek colonies.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During the 8th and 7th centuries, Greek colonies were established at Pithecusae, eventually extending along the south of the Italian Peninsula and the coast of Sicily, an area later known as Magna Graecia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Ionians, Doric colonists, Syracusans, and the Achaeans founded various cities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Greek colonisation placed the Italic peoples in contact with democratic forms of government and high artistic and cultural expressions.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Italy's history goes back to numerous Italic peoples – notably including the ancient Romans, who conquered the Mediterranean world during the Roman Republic and ruled it for centuries during the Roman Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Ancient Rome, a settlement on the River Tiber in central Italy, founded in 753 BC, was ruled for 244 years by a monarchical system.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 509 BC, the Romans, favouring a government of the Senate and the People (SPQR), expelled the monarchy and established an oligarchic republic.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Italian Peninsula, named *Italia*, was consolidated into a unified entity during Roman expansion, the conquest of new territories often at the expense of the other Italic tribes, Etruscans, Celts, and Greeks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] A permanent association, with most of the local tribes and cities, was formed, and Rome began the conquest of Western Europe, North Africa, and the Middle East.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the wake of Julius Caesar's assassination in 44 BC, Rome grew into a massive empire stretching from Britain to the borders of Persia, engulfing the whole Mediterranean basin, in which Greek, Roman, and other cultures merged into a powerful civilisation.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The long reign of the first emperor, Augustus, began an age of peace and prosperity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Roman Italy remained the metropole of the empire, homeland of the Romans and territory of the capital.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The first two centuries of the empire saw a period of unprecedented stability known as the Pax Romana (lit.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Rome reached its greatest territorial extent under Trajan (r.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] 98–117 AD), but a period of increasing trouble and decline began under Commodus (r.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Migration Period, involving large invasions by Germanic peoples, led to the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Roman Empire was among the largest in history, wielding great economical, cultural, political, and military power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] At its greatest extent, it had an area of 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Roman legacy has deeply influenced Western civilisation shaping the modern world.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The widespread use of Romance languages derived from Latin, numerical system, modern Western alphabet and calendar, and the emergence of Christianity as a world religion, are among the many legacies of Roman dominance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Italy fell under the Odoacer's kingdom, and was seized by the Ostrogoths.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Invasions resulted in a chaotic succession of kingdoms and the supposed "Dark Ages".
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The invasion of another Germanic tribe in the 6th century, the Lombards, reduced Byzantine presence and ended the political unity of the peninsula.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The north formed the Lombard kingdom, central-south was also controlled by the Lombards, and other parts remained Byzantine.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Lombard kingdom was absorbed into Francia by Charlemagne in the late 8th century and became the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Franks helped form the Papal States.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Until the 13th century, politics was dominated by relations between the Holy Roman Emperors and the Papacy, with city-states siding with the former (Ghibellines) or with the latter (Guelphs) for momentary advantage.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Germanic emperor and Roman pontiff became the universal powers of medieval Europe.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] However, conflict over the Investiture controversy and between Guelphs and Ghibellines ended the imperial-feudal system in the north, where cities gained independence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1176, the Lombard League of city-states defeated Holy Roman Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, ensuring their independence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] City-states, such as Milan, Florence, and Venice, played a crucially innovative role in financial development by devising banking practices, and enabling new forms of social organisation.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In coastal and southern areas, maritime republics dominated the Mediterranean and monopolised trade to the Orient.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] They were independent thalassocratic city-states, in which merchants had considerable power.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Although oligarchical, the relative political freedom they afforded was conducive to academic and artistic advancement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The best-known maritime republics were Venice, Genoa, Pisa, and Amalfi.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Each had dominion over overseas lands, islands, lands on the Adriatic, Aegean, and Black seas, and commercial colonies in the Near East and North Africa.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Venice and Genoa were Europe's gateways to the East, and producers of fine glass, while Florence was a centre of silk, wool, banking, and jewellery.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The wealth generated enabled the commissioning of large public and private artistic projects.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The republics participated in the Crusades, providing support and transport but primarily pursuing political and commercial opportunities.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the south, Sicily had become an Arab Islamic emirate in the 9th century, thriving until the Italo-Normans conquered it in the late 11th century, together with most of the Lombard and Byzantine principalities of southern Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The region was subsequently divided between the Kingdom of Sicily and Kingdom of Naples.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Black Death of 1348 killed perhaps a third of Italy's population.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During the 1400s and 1500s, Italy was the birthplace and heart of the Renaissance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] This era marked the transition from the medieval period to the modern age and was fostered by the wealth accumulated by merchant cities and the patronage of dominant families.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Italian polities transitioned into regional states ruled by princes who controlled trade and administration, while their courts became prominent centres of the arts and sciences.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] These princedoms were led by political dynasties and merchant families, such as the Medici of Florence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] After the end of the Western Schism, newly elected Pope Martin V returned to the Papal States and restored Italy as the sole centre of Western Christianity.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Medici Bank was made the credit institution of the Papacy, and significant ties were established between the Church and new political dynasties.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1453, despite activity by Pope Nicholas V to support the Byzantines, the city of Constantinople fell to the Ottomans.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] This led to the migration of Greek scholars and texts to Italy, fuelling the rediscovery of Greek humanism.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Humanist rulers such as Federico da Montefeltro and Pope Pius II worked to establish ideal cities, founding Urbino and Pienza.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Pico della Mirandola wrote the *Oration on the Dignity of Man*, considered the manifesto of the Renaissance.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the arts, the Italian Renaissance exercised a dominant influence on European art for centuries, with artists such as Leonardo da Vinci, Botticelli, Michelangelo, Raphael, Giotto, Donatello, and Titian, and architects such as Filippo Brunelleschi, Andrea Palladio, and Donato Bramante.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Italian explorers and navigators from the maritime republics, eager to find an alternative route to the Indies to bypass the Ottomans, offered their services to monarchs of Atlantic countries and played a key role in ushering the Age of Discovery and colonisation of the Americas.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] A defensive alliance known as the Italic League was formed between Venice, Naples, Florence, Milan, and the Papacy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Lorenzo *the Magnificent* de Medici was the Renaissance's greatest patron, his support allowed the League to abort invasion by the Turks.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The alliance, however, collapsed in the 1490s; the invasion of Charles VIII of France initiated a series of wars in the peninsula.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During the High Renaissance, popes such as Julius II (1503–1513) fought for control of Italy against foreign monarchs; Paul III (1534–1549) preferred to mediate between the European powers to secure peace.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the middle of such conflicts, the Medici popes Leo X (1513–1521) and Clement VII (1523–1534) faced the Protestant Reformation in Germany, England and elsewhere.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Papacy launched the Counter-Reformation, whose key events include: the Council of Trent (1545–1563); adoption of the Gregorian calendar; the Jesuit China mission; the French Wars of Religion; end of the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648); and the Great Turkish War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Italian economy declined in the 1600s and 1700s.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During the War of the Spanish Succession (1700–1714), Austria acquired most of the Spanish domains in Italy, namely Milan, Naples and Sardinia; the latter was given to the House of Savoy in exchange for Sicily in 1720.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Later, a branch of the Bourbons ascended to the throne of Sicily and Naples.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] During the Napoleonic Wars, north and central Italy were reorganised as Sister Republics of France and, later, as a Kingdom of Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The south was administered by Joachim Murat, Napoleon's brother-in-law.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] 1814's Congress of Vienna restored the situation of the late 18th century, but the ideals of the French Revolution could not be eradicated, and re-surfaced during the political upheavals that characterised the early 19th century.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The first adoption of the Italian tricolour by an Italian state, the Cispadane Republic, occurred during Napoleonic Italy, following the French Revolution, which advocated national self-determination.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] This event is celebrated by Tricolour Day.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The birth of the Kingdom of Italy was the result of efforts of Italian nationalists and monarchists loyal to the House of Savoy to establish a united kingdom encompassing the entire Italian Peninsula.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] By the mid-19th century, rising Italian nationalism led to revolution.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Following the Congress of Vienna in 1815, the political and social Italian unification movement, or Risorgimento, emerged to unite Italy by consolidating the states and liberating them from foreign control.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] A radical figure was the patriotic journalist Giuseppe Mazzini, founder of the political movement Young Italy in the 1830s, who favoured a unitary republic and advocated a broad nationalist movement.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] 1847 saw the first public performance of "Il Canto degli Italiani", which became the national anthem in 1946.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The most famous member of Young Italy was the revolutionary and general Giuseppe Garibaldi who led the republican drive for unification in southern Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] However, the Italian monarchy of the House of Savoy, in the Kingdom of Sardinia, whose government was led by Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, also had ambitions of establishing a united Italian state.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the context of the 1848 liberal revolutions that swept Europe, an unsuccessful First Italian War of Independence was declared against Austria.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1855, Sardinia became an ally of Britain and France in the Crimean War.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Sardinia fought the Austrian Empire in the Second Italian War of Independence of 1859, with the aid of France, resulting in liberating Lombardy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] On the basis of the Plombières Agreement, the Sardinia ceded Savoy and Nice to France, an event that caused the Niçard exodus.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1860–1861, Garibaldi led the drive for unification in Naples and Sicily.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Teano was the site of a famous meeting between Garibaldi and Victor Emmanuel II, the last king of Sardinia, during which Garibaldi shook Victor Emanuel's hand and hailed him as King of Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Cavour agreed to include Garibaldi's southern Italy in a union with the Kingdom of Sardinia in 1860.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] This allowed the Sardinian government to declare a united Italian kingdom on 17 March 1861, with Victor Emmanuel II as its first king.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1865, the kingdom's capital was moved from Turin to Florence.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In 1866, Victor Emmanuel II, allied with Prussia during the Austro-Prussian War, waged the Third Italian War of Independence, which resulted in Italy annexing Venetia.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Finally, in 1870, as France abandoned Rome during the Franco-Prussian War, the Italians captured the Papal States, unification was completed, and the capital moved to Rome.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] (right), leading figures in unification, became respectively the first King and prime minister of unified Italy.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] Sardinia's constitution was extended to all of Italy in 1861, and provided basic freedoms for the new state; but electoral laws excluded the non-propertied classes.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The new kingdom was governed by a parliamentary constitutional monarchy dominated by liberals.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] As northern Italy quickly industrialised, southern and northern rural areas remained underdeveloped and overpopulated, forcing millions to migrate and fuelling a large and influential diaspora.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] The Italian Socialist Party increased in strength, challenging the traditional liberal and conservative establishment.
[src:community-of-the-ark/italy-p01] In the last two decades of the 19th century, Italy developed into a colonial power by subjugating Eritrea, Somalia, Tripolitania, and Cyrenaica in Africa.
